<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Algeria to sign exploration
deals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK NICHOLSON, Middle East Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALGERIA IS on the verge of signing a fresh batch of oil and gas exploration
agreements, according Mr Nordine Ait Laoussine, the oil minister, who said
the government is discussing new ventures with six foreign companies.
Speaking after last week's Opec meeting, Mr Ait Laoussine said: 'We will be
able to announce very shortly several exploration agreements'.
The oil minister said Algeria's ambitious oil and gas expansion plans,
accelerated late last year by law changes to encourage foreign investment,
could entail investment worth Dollars 20bn by the end of the century in a
drive to boost output to meet European demand.
Mr Ait Laoussine also said Algeria would open a bidding process for up to 12
new oil concessions in July. He added that, if should talks with some of the
six companies currently involved in negotiations - including US, European
and Japanese groups - were not be concluded by then, he might include blocs
in the next round.
He hoped to offer fresh territory for bidding every six months. 'We would
like to cover all the sedimentary areas with bidders,' he said.
The country - which is also a leading producer of gas, liquified natural gas
and condensates - hopes to raise output from some 1.8m b/d of oil equivalent
to some 2.5m b/d by the turn of the century. Mr Ait Laoussine said Algeria
had signed contracts to export almost 60bn cubic metres of natural gas a
year - the most the country can comfortably sustain, he explained - and was
expanding facilities to meet that target.
With reserves of 3 trillion (million million) cu m of gas, the minister said
recently that Algeria hoped to become Europe's major gas supplier over the
next decade. In Vienna he pointed out that Algeria needed to explore gas
fields in the country's south which, he said, had been largely neglected.
On oil, Mr Ait Laoussine said there was a 'definite need to increase the
exploration effort' in Algeria, which at present pumps 770,000 barrels a
day.
Official studies estimate that Algeria faces a decline in sustainable output
to between 500,000 and 300,000 b/d by early next century without new oil
finds. Algeria presently has just over 9bn barrels of exploitable reserves.
The government late last year substantially revised its foreign investment
laws in the hope of attracting foreign capital into its hitherto protected
oil sector. The changes permitted output sharing agreements, improved
exploration terms and cut tax and royalty rates.
Atlantic Richfield (Arco) this month became the first foreign company since
the law changes to sign contracts with Sonatrach, the state oil company, to
explore for oil and gas.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
