<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / International Company News: O&amp;Y bank creditors post gains
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BANK of Montreal (BMO) and Bank of Nova Scotia, Canada's third and fourth
biggest banks respectively, lifted second-quarter earnings despite their
sizeable exposures to troubled property developer Olympia &amp; York.
BMO, which disclosed CDollars 318m (USDollars 267.2m) in loans to O&amp;Y,
boosted net earnings to CDollars 143.5m, or CDollars 1.07 a share, in the
three months to April 30, from CDollars 128.4m, or CDollars 1.01, a year
earlier.
The improvement was due largely to a slower rise in expenses than in
revenues, and to a substantial growth in lending volumes, especially to
small and mid-sized businesses. Total assets have jumped by almost 8 per
cent in the past year to CDollars 104.2bn.
BNS's earnings advanced to CDollars 171m, or 75 cents a share, from CDollars
163.3m, or 73 cents, in the same period last year. The bank ascribed the
rise to wider margins as interest rates continued to decline.
BNS has lifted its fiscal 1992 loan loss provisions by CDollars 200m, or 45
per cent, to reflect its exposure to O&amp;Y and to other troubled borrowers.
Its exposure to O&amp;Y stands at CDollars 630m.
Its second-quarter provision of CDollars 110m is unchanged from the previous
three months. The provision in the second quarter of 1991 was CDollars 85m.
Non-performing loans, net of provisions, rose to CDollars 1.87bn on April 30
from CDollars 1.74bn three months earlier. The bank did not disclose how
much of this increase was accounted for by O&amp;Y loans.
BMO has classified its entire O&amp;Y portfolio as non-performing, but has left
its forecast for fiscal 1992 loan losses unchanged at CDollars 500m. The
bank said that its loans to O&amp;Y were secured by specific office buildings,
which continue to generate cash flow, and by listed marketable securities.
It is not involved in the Canary Wharf project in London or in any of O&amp;Y's
large syndicated financings.
Although they are among O&amp;Y's biggest lenders, the Canadian banks are
generally well-equipped to absorb substantial losses. BMO reported that its
risk-weighted capital-to-assets ratio improved in the second quarter to 9.1
per cent from 8.5 per cent three months earlier. BNS's capital ratio has
edged up to 8.6 per cent from 8.5 per cent. Olympia &amp; York's creditors are
gradually stripping away the secrecy that was once the property developer's
hallmark.
The Toronto-based company, whose Canadian operations were placed under court
protection two weeks ago, has made public for the first time the cash flows
of its Canadian properties.
The data is contained in a 26-page affidavit submitted in response to a
court order which was granted last week at the request of the creditors. The
company was also due to provide various groups of lenders with more detailed
information by late yesterday, including projections of future cash flows.
</TEXT>
