<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / UK Company News: Mercury Asset advances 15% despite
provisions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MERCURY ASSET Manage-ment, the fund management group 75 per cent owned by SG
Warburg, achieved a 15 per cent rise in pre-tax profits last year despite
substantial provisions on two investments.
Pre-tax profits in the year to March 31 rose from Pounds 56.4m to Pounds
65.1m, reflecting the group's success in holding down costs. While turnover
jumped by Pounds 14.6m to Pounds 154m, costs rose by less than Pounds 1m to
Pounds 99.6m.
Mr Peter Stormonth Darling, chairman, said that investment in systems in
previous years to make the group's back office operations more efficient had
accounted for the low cost increase.
However, the group announced provisions of about Pounds 5m on two
investments at March 31, holding back its advance. Some Pounds 3m of this
was a write-down on its investment in Jupiter, a fund management group in
which MAM bought a 27 per cent stake for Pounds 7m last year. About half of
that provision might be written back because the value of MAM's holding had
recovered since the year-end, Mr Stormonth Darling said.
A further provision of more than Pounds 1m was made against a holding by MAM
in Isosceles, which it had taken on to its own books when unable to place
the shares with investment clients.
Funds under management rose by Pounds 2.7bn to Pounds 40bn. The Pounds 2bn
of new money under management, down from the record Pounds 3bn taken on the
previous year, reflected the slower rate at which cash was flowing into UK
pension funds.
Earnings were 25.4p (22.8p) basic and 25.1p (22.1p) diluted. A final
dividend of 8.9p is proposed, for a total of 11.5p (10p adjusted).
</TEXT>
