FT  27 MAY 92 / Brown Shipley to raise Pounds 43m in disposal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BROWN SHIPLEY, the merchant banking group, is to sell two of its
subsidiaries. The group, which posted pre-tax losses of Pounds 3.34m in the
year to March 31, 1991, confirmed yesterday that overall losses for the year
ending March 31, 1992 would be 'substantial'.
It will earn some Pounds 33m from the sale of its profitable insurance
broking arm to Holmwoods Group, a company formed by the arm's senior
management. The sale of Brown Shipley's offshore company to Standard Bank
Investment Corporation of South Africa (SBIC) will net a further Pounds
10.25m.
Holmwoods, which has been advised by J O Hambro Magan, is to pay Pounds 30m
in cash plus two deeply discounted loan notes with aggregate nominal value
of Pounds 3m and final redemption dates in 1997 and 1998.
CINVen, manager of Pounds 600m of pension funds for British Coal, British
Rail and Barclays Bank Pension Funds, will provide 70 per cent of the equity
backing for the venture. Senior debt behind the deal has been underwritten
by the Bank of Scotland.
Holmwoods specialises in providing insurances for private schools and
colleges in the UK and the US, where it trades as AWG Dewar. Its other
activities include marine, corporate and personal insurance broking.
The insurance broking subsidiary was a profitable part of the Brown Shipley
group. Unaudited profits in the year to March 31, 1992 amounted to Pounds
3.5m, including exceptional items of Pounds 340,000, when shareholders'
funds amounted to Pounds 5.1m.
SBIC's payment for the offshore company is subject to an adjustment based on
the net assets of the offshore group, which specialises in banking,
stockbroking, investment management and fiduciary services, primarily from
its base in Jersey.
Discussions are also taking place with Woodchester Investments about the
terms of the sale of Lease Management Services, Brown Shipley's leasing
subsidiary. A memorandum of understanding has been exchanged.
Brown Shipley said its 'accounts for the full year ending March 31, 1992
would include sharply increased provisions for bad and doubtful debts,
resulting in a substantial overall loss. Against this background the
directors will not be recommending a final dividend.'
Observer, Page 19
