<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Japanese computer makers fall below expected earnings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN'S computer and semi-conductor makers yesterday reported
worse-than-expected earnings for the fiscal year just ended.
The parent companies of NEC, Toshiba, Mitsubishi Electric and Fujitsu
announced falls in pre-tax profits ranging from 43.1 per cent to 68.6 per
cent. They blamed the poor performance on a weak semiconductor market and,
in particular, falling prices for the latest generation of memory chip, the
4Mbit, on which they may never recoup their investments.
Sharp reported a smaller drop in profits - 11.9 per cent - although along
with other makers of consumer products, it reported a fall in demand for
audio-visual equipment.
Most of the chip makers' factories are running at well below capacity.
Toshiba, for example, produces about 300m of the 4Mbit chips, instead of the
planned 500m each month. In the past year, the price of those chips has more
than halved, to Y1,400 (Pounds 5.90) each.
As a result, Japanese companies which have dominated the memory chip market
in recent years, are cutting back on new semiconductor investment.
NEC said the industry had been hit by global recession and falls in domestic
capital expenditure and consumer spending.
Fujitsu, the world's second largest computer manufacturer, is hoping for a
25 per cent rise in profits, to Y50bn.
Mitsubishi Electric reported flat parent sales of heavy machinery,
industrial products and automation equipment. Air-conditioners were the
best-selling consumer line, but audio-visual equipment sales were weak.
Japan's work ethic, Page 4
