<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / S&amp;P gloomy on US property losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
STANDARD &amp; POOR's, the credit rating service, yesterday offered a gloomy
assessment of the likely impact on US banks of loan losses from the
depressed US commercial property market.
The S&amp;P study warned that notwithstanding improved first-quarter 1992
earnings at a number of US banks, the worst was not yet over.
S&amp;P said it believed 'that the problem loan workout period will be
protracted and that the losses will have a long tail, reaching substantially
higher levels than they have to date'.
The report sought to dispel the idea that the effect of the worldwide
property depression on the US banking industry was waning.
The recent bankruptcy filings by Olympia &amp; York of Canada were cited by S&amp;P
as 'a vivid confirmation that real estate (property) markets have not begun
to recover or stabilise'.
Senior US bank executives have said in recent months they expect the level
of bad debt provisions caused by commercial property loans to remain at the
same level this year as in 1991.
But the S&amp;P report claimed that reserves at many banks are not yet adequate
to cover prospective commercial property losses.
S&amp;P predicted that 'the overhang of losses will continue to be a significant
drain on (banking) industry earnings over the next few years'.
The report said that S&amp;P's outlook for bank ratings remains stable, with
several banks unlikely to receive a ratings upgrade in the near term.
S&amp;P cited the experience of banks in Texas during the late 1980s property
slump as a worst-case scenario, and noted that loan write-offs at some Texas
institutions reached the level of 30 per cent of commercial property loan
portfolios.
The ratings service described as 'disturbing' that the level of
non-performing property loans at New York City banks was reaching the 40 per
cent range.
Loan losses would not be as high in other regions as they were in Texas and
the southwest, and should represent about 15 per cent of the original loan
portfolio value of most banks.
The loan losses could, however, reach the level of 25 per cent of
outstanding property loans at some banks, S&amp;P said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 21
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-6032</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CE0AWAFHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920527
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / EC weakens environment plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Community's position at next week's Earth Summit in Rio de
Janeiro looks set to fall well short of what environment commissioner Carlo
Ripa di Meana has proposed, and his own attendance at the summit was last
night in doubt.
Environment ministers of the 12 yesterday agreed to sign the Climate Change
convention, due to be agreed in Rio, but they did not agree to endorse
politically the European Commission's plan to tax energy as a means of
curbing CO emissions, even though no EC state opposed the proposal.
Nor were they able to agree on a timetable for nearly doubling development
aid to a minimum of 0.7 per cent of gross domestic product to help
developing countries adopt more environmentally sound development
strategies.
Taken together, this is a limp posture when set against what Mr Ripa de
Meana had defined as the minimum 'dowry' the Community should take to Rio.
The Commission's plan is to stabilise CO emissions at 1990 levels by 2000,
through an energy tax equivalent to Dollars 10 a barrel of oil equivalent.
Mr Ripa di Meana says the EC can only deliver half that target without a
tax.
The plan won strong support yesterday from Germany, Denmark, the
Netherlands, Luxembourg and Italy. The first four attacked the Commission
for making introduction of the tax conditional on the US and Japan adopting
similar measures.
France and the UK reserved their position behind procedure, since the
Commission overshot its deadline in producing the detailed draft directive,
which it will look at today.
'The UK position remains that when we see it, we will study it in detail,'
Mr Michael Howard, UK environment secretary, said of the tax plan.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 20
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-6033</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CE0AWAFGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920527
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / The Lex Column: SG Warburg
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
It may be gratifying for SG Warburg to unveil Pounds 71m of previously
hidden reserves, but that also creates a large slice of additional capital
on which it has to make an acceptable return. Yesterday's annual results
show that only Pounds 3m would have been added to hidden reserves in 1991-92
had they still been in place. So the extra capital may prove something of a
millstone, although Warburg will need to be well-capitalised to meet EC
securities company regulations. That in turn creates a requirement for a
steady flow of large issues, whatever conditions in the market, if the
capital is to be used efficiently. Net return on capital last year was only
12 per cent.
Mercury Asset Management's provisions against its investments in Jupiter
Tyndall and Isosceles are a real but transitory embarrassment. More worrying
is the fact that, thanks to pension fund holidays, it only attracted some
Pounds 2bn of new money last year. Since it cannot continue to cut costs for
ever, MAM must break into the nascent European pension fund market to secure
future growth.
The chances are that a smooth operator such as Warburg can cope with these
problems better than most. But the road ahead is difficult. A yield of 4 per
cent offers only limited compensation for investors, even if the scare
surrounding February's so-called profit warning was overdone.
</TEXT>
