<PROFILE>_AN-CE0AWAFFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920527
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / The Lex Column: Mountleigh
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
It is not entirely clear why the banks should have pulled the plug on
Mountleigh, as opposed to any of the other walking wounded in the UK
property sector. The lenders, to be sure, already have their hands on most
of the available security, and have no obvious incentive to throw Pounds 56m
of good money after potentially obstreperous bondholders. Mountleigh,
though, is hardly unique in this respect. Perhaps in the end patience simply
ran out with a company whose conspicuous extravagance had become a symbol of
the late 1980s and whose top-heavy 14 man board was disparagingly but aptly
described by one small shareholder at the last annual meeting as a football
team with three reserves.
Judging by the market's calm reaction to the news yesterday, it may be that
the wider implications are indeed slight. After all, everyone knew that
Mountleigh's assets had to be sold to repay its debts: all that has happened
is that the administrator rather than the company will now get on with the
task. The problem with this cosy theory is that the timetable for disposals
will now presumably be that much tighter, the risk being that today's forced
sellers ultimately become the market. With very few signs of a pick-up in
demand vendors in the commercial property sector may prove to be behaving as
unrealistically as home owners throughout most of last year. The banks have
to balance the cost of further rescues against the damage to confidence and
the impact on their balance sheets of letting other companies go bust. It is
a delicate and dangerous game.
</TEXT>
