<PROFILE>_AN-CE0AWAFDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920527
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / The Lex Column: Dowsing the grid
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Whatever the outcome of the latest government inquiry, a national grid for
the UK water industry is likely to remain a distant prospect. Practical
objections aside, it is perhaps worth recalling that the principal
attraction of privatising water was to remove the industry's capital
spending requirements from public sector finances. It is scarcely
conceivable that the government would approve the huge increases in spending
needed to build a national supply network. By way of example, the 50 miles
of the London ring main is costing Thames Water around Pounds 250m.
Granted, the issue of who would pay for the grid is clouded, but there is
little chance of the companies stumping up. As the forthcoming results
season will remind them, consumers already face steady real increases in
water bills. The case for further rises is unlikely to appeal to
politicians. Nor would investors in water shares have much to cheer about.
In addition to capital costs, there would be ongoing operating expenses for
pumping water around the country. Should UK rainfall return to historic
levels, a large project might end in embarrassment.
All the same, the politicians' surge of interest could have beneficial
effects. If the regulator agreed, water companies' spending on improvements
to their leaking underground pipes could be brought forward at the expense
of other work. In time, that would ease the supply problem.
A faster introduction of metering might have the same effect on consumption.
Water company chairmen have long maintained that their biggest problem is
consumers' wasteful attitude to the resource. Changing that is perhaps a
sufficient long-term challenge for the industry. More immediately, the
shares will doubtless be supported by a regulatory regime that still allows
dividends to be increased at roughly twice the average market rate.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
