<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / EC moves closer to trade ban on Serbia as Major speaks out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, LAURA SILBER and JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WARSAW, BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Community last night moved closer to a trade ban and other
sanctions against Serbia as officials of the 12 member nations, meeting in
Brussels, agreed on recommendations to ministers.
The drive for sanctions gained further momentum as Mr John Major, visiting
central Europe, condemned the role of Serbian forces in provoking ethnic
conflict in breakaway Yugoslav republics. Before leaving Warsaw for Prague,
the prime minister called for mandatory United Nations sanctions to force an
end to the fighting.
British officials travelling with Mr Major said ambassadors of UN Security
Council nations in New York had prepared a draft UN sanctions resolution
against Serbia. But France was said to be resisting the inclusion of oil
trade in any package of sanctions.
The officials gathered in Brussels left open whether the EC should act alone
or through the UN. Their recommended package of sanctions will be
scrutinised at a meeting of EC ambassadors today, but EC ministers might not
meet until next week to decide on it.
Mr James Baker, US secretary of state, called at the weekend for tough
sanctions against Serbia, and both the US and Canada have cut air links with
Belgrade. EC countries and the US have already announcing withdrawal of
diplomats from Belgrade.
Mr Major made clear Britain was pressing for mandatory measures including an
oil embargo, a break in civil air links with Belgrade and more general trade
sanctions.
He was aware when he made his remarks that France is reluctant to agree to
significant sanctions. But he indicated Britain was determined to press
ahead regardless. His calculation is that Paris will not in the end be able
to resist international pressure for sanctions.
Mr Major set out a series of conditions which the west should demand before
lifting a threat against Serbia. They included a ceasefire in the breakaway
republic of Bosnia-Hercegovina, Serbian action to control its irregular
forces, resumption of constitutional talks and guarantees to let refugees
return home.
Echoing the hard line taken by Washington on international sanctions, Mr
Major demanded also that troops of the Yugoslav federal army be withdrawn
from the republic of Croatia.
Diplomats in Brussels said France wanted any trade embargo, particularly on
oil, to be channelled through the Security Council. France argued that
because the EC supplied only about 10 per cent of Serbia's oil, an embargo
would work only if backed by such countries as Iran, China and Russia.
In an effort to head off the campaign for sanctions, Serbia promised to 'do
its utmost' to get humanitarian aid to Bosnia.
At the same time Mr Andrei Kozyrev, the Russian foreign minister, announced
a deal in Sarajevo to reopen the blockaded city's airport. He said a
ceasefire would take effect today so that emergency supplies of food and
medicines could be flown in.
The airport has been under blockade since early April, first by the federal
army and now by Serbian irregulars.
</TEXT>
