FT  27 MAY 92 / Observer: Driving force
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The last amateur cricketer to lead a county championship winning side, Colin
Ingleby-Mackenzie, faces a challenge of a different order as head of the
management buy-out team at insurance brokers Holmwoods.
Ingleby-Mackenzie, who won national sporting fame when he led Hampshire's
successful side during the late 1950s and early 1960s, is skippering the
Pounds 33m move for Holmwoods, a subsidiary of merchant banking group Brown
Shipley which has hitherto specialised in finding insurance for private
schools. Already solidly profitable, it seems well placed to take advantage
of the increasing flexibility with which public-sector schools are being
run.
Among the 50-strong management team involved in the buy-out is another
former county captain, Nick Pocock, a successor of Ingleby-Mackenzie at
Hampshire, while Carl Openshaw, director of finance and development, is a
third cricketing buff - albeit a Kentishman.
