FT  27 MAY 92 / Observer: Class-conscious
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A charter has come to the aid of Citizen Major.
On his first foreign trip since the election victory, the prime minister is
travelling around Central Europe on an aircraft more used to ferrying
holidaymakers on cut-price package tours. When Major decided three weeks ago
to travel to Poland, Hungary and Czechoslovakia, the RAF regretted there
were simply no VC10s available to accommodate him and his entourage. So John
and Norma find themselves on an ancient BAC 1-11 chartered from British Air
Ferries.
When introduced in the 1960s, the aircraft was undoubtedly ahead of its time
but in more recent years has been consigned to the Stansted-Jersey holiday
run.
Major may be unphased by having to sit in economy just a few rows ahead of
the travelling press. But the class-conscious political hacks have already
pledged themselves to decorous silence if on future trips the man of the
people opts for an aeroplane more appropriate to their status.
