FT  27 MAY 92 / Observer: Pohl's golden opportunity
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Canadian financiers with fingers in the property pie are hardly flavour of
the month among the international banking fraternity these days. But Peter
Munk, Toronto entrepreneur par excellence, is clearly different. How else
has the smooth-talking, fine-wine-loving Munk managed to lure Karl Otto Pohl
onto the board of his gold, oil and property holding company Horsham
Corporation?
Since stepping down from the Bundesbank, Pohl has lined up an impressive
string of blue-chip directorships - including Bertelsmann, Unilever and
Royal Dutch Shell. Having turned down hosts of other worthy causes, he was
obviously in the market for a touch of excitement.
But what, in turn, can the owner of American Barrick, a leading North
American gold producer, and Clark Oil, a US Midwest oil refiner, want with a
former German central banker, however noted?
A Hungarian emigre who has been in Canada for more than 30 years, Munk still
retains a soft spot for Europe and Europeans. He has a ski chalet at
Klosters, and another prominent German, Nato secretary-general Manfred
Worner, was a guest of the Munks on his most recent Canadian trip.
Never dull on the subject of French wines, Munk would like Pohl's reputed
ability to be able to distinguish between 200 sorts of grappa.
And while he would not primarily be seeking advice on the gold or oil
markets, Munk must undoubtedly be hoping the new big name addition to the
board will grease the wheels of a recent foray into Germany.
Horsham owns 195 hectares on the outskirts of Berlin which it wants to turn
into a business park and entertainment complex and has its eyes on other
properties. Pohl's help should be invaluable in the search for financial
partners - and tenants.
</TEXT>
