<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Leading Article: Italy's need for reform
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
IT SOMETIMES seems to take a shock to make Italians realise that urgent
action is required to avert a national crisis. It needed such a shock, in
the form of popular indignation at the murder of the courageous anti-mafia
magistrate, Mr Giovanni Falcone, to shame Italy's squabbling politicians
into electing a new president.
The insults hurled by mourners at Mr Falcone's funeral against leading
politicians, including Mr Spadolini, the justice minister, reflected growing
public outrage at the incapacity of the authorities to clamp down on the
mafia's overlords. Thanks mainly to the efforts of individual judges
prepared to risk their lives, successive crime and corruption scandals have
brought to light the links between the mafia and some sections of the
political establishment and the police.
Until recently, corrupt practices were associated mainly with the Christian
Democratic party, the ruling party throughout most of the post-Second World
War era. But arrests made in the latest corruption scandal in Milan have
demonstrated that the cancer has spread to other political groups,
particularly former prime minister Bettino Craxi's Socialist party.
So it is hardly any wonder that the Italian people have become more and more
disillusioned with the old guard of politicians. The voters fired a powerful
shot across their bows in the general election at the beginning of last
month, when they deprived the outgoing four-party coalition of its overall
parliamentary majority. The long-dominant Christian Democrats won less than
30 per cent of the overall vote for the first time.
Signally failed
The result was widely interpreted not only as a rejection of the old
political parties - no fewer than 16 parties are represented in the new
parliament - but as a desire for a reform of a political system which has
signally failed to provide stable government.
The farcical scenes which characterised the early rounds of the presidential
election this month were a reversion to old-style Italian political
practices and a negation of what the electorate appears to want. But the one
positive outcome of the assassination of Mr Falcone is that it has brought
the politicians to their senses. The business of forming a new government
can now begin in earnest.
The choice of Mr Oscar Luigi Scalfaro as president appears to be a good one.
While he is a veteran member of the Christian Democratic party, his support
has come from all parties. Above all Mr Scalfaro has a reputation for
incorruptibility and is thus the man for the moment. Although his powers as
head of state are strictly limited, he has considerable influence on the
government-building process. That is important at a time when speed and good
judgment are of the essence.
Main tasks
One of the new president's main tasks will be to persuade the politicians
and the country as a whole that Italy has no more time to waste. Though a
signatory of last year's Maastricht Treaty, Italy has yet to persuade its
European partners that it can fulfil either the conditions of the projected
economic and monetary union or the political union. It is still a very long
way from meeting any of the economic convergence criteria laid down for full
membership of Emu. More fundamentally, its partners must wonder whether it
will be able to enforce the directives and other Community-wide legal
instruments laws agreed collectively.
The remedies are not difficult to find. Tough measures must be taken to
bring the public deficit and debt under control, to cut subsidies to state
industry and to reform the pensions system. Equally important is the fight
against corruption and gangsterism. An important part of the solution will
be an agressive programme of privatisation. This can only be done by a
strong government, requiring a radical reform of the present electoral
system.
The fundamental condition for achieving all this is political will, which
has so far been lacking. That resolution may now be provided by pressure
from a people who seem finally to have had enough of political instability
and corruption. Italy's politicians must be made to understand that there is
no room for further procrastination.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 18
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-6046</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CE0AWAE3FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920527
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Arts: Jenufa - Opera at Glyndebourne
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAX LOPPERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Glyndebourne brings back its 1989 production of Jenufa. Three years ago it
was already a noble achievement; now it must be deemed one of the festival's
unarguable triumphs, superlatively well sung, played, acted and conducted -
an experience of 'small-house' Janacek opera, close-meshed in ensemble, that
proves almost too much to bear.
Stumbling back at the end, blinded by tears and stirred to the marrow, into
the civilised Glyndebourne world of Pimms and picnic baskets may be one of
life's odder experiences. It is certainly one of British opera's most
meaningful and valuable.
The tone of the revival - urgent in momentum, never driven in pace - is set
by the musical direction of Yakov Kreizberg, the young Russian making his
British debut. On this showing he would appear to possess a talent for
genuinely dramatic opera-conducting of a rare order.
The sonorities drawn from the LPO are no longer refulgently Straussian and
string-based, as they were first time round, but athletic,
woodwind-dominated - lots of lyrically insistent oboe and plangent bassoon
to the fore - and stamped by an airy clarity of texture that lets through
the voices and allows the angular phrase-nuggets to soar.
The cleaned-up Mackerras-Tyrrell edition used by Glyndebourne sounds not
just leanly magnificent but fiercely right; the pulse-beat of the music,
keen yet steady, is made indistinguishable from that of Nikolaus Lehnhoff's
severely beautiful staging.
The two leading sopranos of 1989, Roberta Alexander in the title role and
Anja Silja as the sextoness, have returned to the production, to its
incalculable benefit. They find in its acutely judged confines an ideal
space for creating character through voices and bodies.
Miss Silja's gaunt tragic radiance was from the first on the highest level
of music-drama, a triumph of sweeping imaginative perception fully realised;
now Miss Alexander is every bit her equal, with sweet yet sinewy singing and
a heartbreaking quiet warmth of bearing.
The two play to each other's strengths with glorious freedom, subtlety and
generosity. When they are on stage together, alone or alongside Menai Davies
(grandmother), Angela Hickey (mayoral wife) and Elen ap Robert (Karolka),
all superb, Jenufa demands to be accounted the great Woman's Opera.
But since Kim Begley's heroically sung Laca and Kurt Schreibmayer's trimly
handsome Steva (a touch unsteady of voice at climaxes) arrive at the same
full-blooded roundness of characterisation, it is in the end Janacek's
sublime honesty of vision that Glyndebourne celebrates.
In repertory until July 17
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 17
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-6047</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CE0AWAE2FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920527
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Arts: Philadelphia Orchestra
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW CLEMENTS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
For the London stopover on their European tour the Philadelphia Orchestra
brought a refreshingly unhackneyed programme to the Festival Hall. There was
none of box-office-safe Beethoven or Brahms with which visiting orchestras
too often shore up their concerts - the big romantic symphony was Skryabin's
Second, and the orchestral showpieces placed before it were Elgar's concert
overture In the South and Casella's Paganiniana.
The current tour is the last the orchestra will undertake with Riccardo Muti
as Music Director; he leaves at the end of the current season to be replaced
by Wolfgang Sawallisch. On the evidence of Monday's concert Muti will
bequeath to his successor an ensemble as fine as any in the world at
present.
There are no detectable faults in any department of the orchestra; the sound
is supple and refined, founded upon a wonderfully homogeneous string
section, with wind principals, brass as much as woodwind, of limpid phrasing
and elegant individuality. The personality of the orchestra is never
intrusive; it offers carte blanche to a conductor who knows his stuff to
apply his own characterisations and nuances. The sound world on offer,
though, is not one to suit precisely every part of the orchestral repertory.
In this particular programme that mattered not at all, particularly with
Muti's bracing attacks on rhythms and dynamics to add contours and life to
the immaculate surfaces.
Casella's four-movement suite was an innocuous start. Commissioned to
celebrate the centenary of the Vienna Philharmonic in 1942, it was hardly
born under a lucky star, and does little but run the departments of the
orchestra through some showy neoclassical paces.
In the South has long been a Muti party-piece; he conducted it in London
during his years with the Philharmonia, and has preserved the freshness and
vigour of his approach intact. There was a real Mediterranean tang to its
flavours, intense theatricality in its extraordinary depiction of the might
of the Roman empire, a daring sweep and thrust to the phrasing. It is the
most (Richard) Straussian of all Elgar's works, and delivered without
English pastoral preconceptions becomes a thrilling piece of orchestral
description.
The longueurs of Skryabin's Second are less easy to transmute; a work which
never says anything in eight bars which could profitably be extended to 80
needs all the care and attention a conductor can provide. Muti gave the
impression of believing in every one of its blasts of rhetoric; even the C
major finale, piling banality upon banality, was given its full measure.
Earlier the langourous melodies and queasy modulations had been sifted and
coloured most beautifully by the Philadelphia strings; a better case for the
work could not have been made.
After such a peerless demonstration of orchestral virtuosity, an encore was
inevitable - an orchestral arrangement of a piano Notturno by Giuseppe
Martucci, a favourite piece of Toscanini as Muti told us from the rostrum,
and played here with hushed eloquence and burnished tone.
</TEXT>
