<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Arts: Malvern Festival
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD FAIRMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Malvern hills threatened to ring with unaccustomed music at the weekend,
as thousands of hippies gathered for an impromptu festival. This is the home
of Edward Elgar and the uninvited visitors had taken over the very area
where the great English composer conceived some of his finest music.
By coincidence it was also the central weekend of the official Malvern
Festival. As one might expect, Elgar is traditionally the presiding spirit
in the hall at Great Malvern which bears his name. This year, however, the
festival programme has featured Robert Simpson as Composer in Residence.
Four of his works received premieres, funded entirely by the festival after
other sources failed to come up with finance: a symphony, a string quartet
and concertos for flute and cello.
Simpson has always been concerned with the renewal of classical forms and
these four pieces have imposed on them his usual rigour of form.
The Eleventh Symphony is lighter than its immediate predecessors. Simpson
has written for a chamber orchestra and made a conscious effort to keep the
textures transparent.
The symphony lasts half an hour. It is in two movements, the first slow and
moody like Shostakovich, the second playful at first, then forcefully
dramatic. The teasing final pay-off, in which the brooding music is swept
aside with a flick of the wrist, recalls the end of the Fourth Symphony of
Beethoven.
The symphony was written for the conductor, Matthew Taylor, towards whom the
composer was generous with his praise, but the City of London Sinfonia
performed as if it had yet to get the technical difficulties under its belt.
On Sunday, the orchestra returned to give the first performance of the Flute
Concerto, now conducted by Richard Hickox and with Susan Milan the eloquent
soloist.
Of the two premieres which I heard, this was the more attractive. The flute
writing is delightful, delicately balanced between decoration and substance;
the structure is novel.
From a fanciful scherzo-like opening, the concerto slowly winds down until
it metamorphoses into an intimate quintet, producing a thought-provoking
ending as the music turns ever more pensively in upon itself.
The loss made on mounting the premieres means the festival will be returning
to more traditional fare next year. Elgar is the likely focus of attention -
bands of roving hippies notwithstanding.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 17
</PAGE>
</DOC>
