<DOCNO>FT922-6049</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CE0AWAE0FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920527
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Arts: Spitting contest for grown men - Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Does soccer sometimes seem to you little more than a spitting contest for
grown men? Does it strike you as absurd that they spend all that energy
producing, typically, a one-nil score? Are you appalled at the way tackled
players fling themselves to the ground and go through pantomimes of agony
until they realise nobody is watching? Then, like me, your first reaction to
the news that ITV was stitched up by BSkyB (or Sky as we shall call it) with
the sly assistance of the BBC ('Yes let's sling a brick through their window
why don't you') may have been quiet satisfaction. At last they are taking
away this infantile exhibition and sticking it on a separate channel where
we won't have to watch it.
There are, of course, second thoughts. For a start, there is a lot of soccer
outside the Premiere League and, as the BBC proved when it lost the
athletics and boxing contracts which had previously given it the top
contests, it is possible to make fairly impressive bricks with low grade
straw, if you happen to be an outstanding programme maker with a lot of
experience and a well established tradition of sustaining the sports
infrastructure.
So, even viewers without a dish are likely to find quite a bit of this awful
game still on their screens. Secondly, though the consensus is that Sky has
achieved a great coup, the proof of the pudding will be in the eating:
Pounds 304m is a huge sum, and not all the big sports deals of recent years
have proved profitable to television.
Most significantly, perhaps, the deal is the most vivid example yet of what
the Thatcherites meant when they talked about bringing free market economics
to television. In the very week that the BBC's top management was told yet
again that it would have to cut more staff and introduce further economies
to justify its claim on the licence fee - Pounds 80 a year, or less than
Pounds 6.70 a month for two television channels and five radio networks - we
learn from Mr Rupert Murdoch's Sunday Times that, thanks to the Sky coup,
'by next year homes wanting to watch football are likely to be paying an
average of Pounds 22 a month for the privilege' to Mr Murdoch's Sky TV.
Thus what was, until recently, available as cheap viewing for everybody
under the much derided BBC/ITV duopoly is to become a Pounds 22-a-month
'privilege' for those who can afford it. Is this really an improvement in
British life? If the deal does work, dish sales do shoot up, and Sky does
bring in that pay system, two groups will presumably benefit greatly: the
clubs in the Premiere League, and Sky shareholders. . . which include those
of us on the FT who took up share options in the parent company, Pearson,
long before it became one of Sky's main shareholders.
It would be short-sighted or dishonest, or both, to pretend changes of this
sort are due exclusively to the actions of politicians. The days of
wavelength scarcity with the resultant automatic domination of public
service broadcasting are gone. It is possible today to have entire channels
dedicated to sports: anyone with a Sky dish pointing at the Astra satellite
is already receiving three. The relationship between viewers and, say,
football clubs is affected as much by developing technology as by
politicians. However, politicians can greatly help or hinder, and it is
impossible to avoid the feeling the present lot are intent upon helping
outfits such as Sky.
I had hoped to be able to turn from soccer to the arts, specifically to
BBC2's season under the awkward umbrella title 'Commissions And
Collaborations', and declare 'There, you see? Thanks to its popular base
that's what the BBC can do, and does do, and ought to be encouraged to go on
doing, because nobody else has ever managed to do it better, and nobody else
has done it (well or badly) at such low unit costs'. But of course life is
rarely so simple: 'Commissions And Collaborations' turns out to be a
decidedly odd mixture.
Some of its items are certainly fresh and exciting. For instance Cross
Channel, a half hour programme choreographed by Lea Anderson and directed by
Margaret Williams, is one of the best television dance programmes (dance
specifically created for television) that I have ever seen. The all-female
Cholmondeleys go to Calais while the all-male Featherstonehaughs camp on the
white cliffs of Dover, and around this Anderson creates a delightfully funny
ballet of the banal: the men using all the gestures of the car packers on
the ferry, the women reading newspapers on the boat, the men building human
pyramids the way people do on beaches.
Everything works, from the music to the brilliant ice-cream colours, and
above all the way in which television is exploited to expand the potential
of dance. Location shooting is a huge advantage. At one point the girls, for
some reason in white debs' dresses from the 1950s, dance in a hotel corridor
in Calais while the boys are performing on the English cliffs: the music is
the sole common strand, but that is all that is needed to bridge the
Channel.
Nearly the same can be said for two or three of the five-minute programmes
in the 12-strong Dance House which started last night and is currently
appearing each night at 7.55. Programme 5 created by Belinda Neave and Peter
Mumford makes good use of television's tricks: slo-mo, constant replay, a
sequence in which a dancer goes tumbling down a passage, the invisible edits
making it seem as though the passage and consequently the dance are endless.
In No. 10 Kim Brandstrup and Ross MacGibbon offer a 5-minute Cinderella,
reminding us (and, it must be hoped, some of the other programme makers)
that narrative is not something to be ashamed about. Best of all is the last
piece, by Aletta Collins which, like Cross Channel, has the advantage of
location filming, good music and humour.
Too many of the others were made by people who seem to have been unaware
that they were working in television. Had they spent an hour watching the
pop videos on MTV or Lifestyle's Satellite Jukebox, both available to owners
of Astra dishes, they would have seen Wacko Jacko or his sister, or Mylene
Farmer, and realised that there is already a lot of dance expertise on
television.
In The Mystery Of Dr Martinu, Ken Russell appeared to have retrogressed to
some point before A Song Of Summer, his unforgettable programme about Delius
made for the BBC 24 years ago. The Billboard Project seems downright
contrary; it may make sense for a broadcasting organisation to support
orchestras since they make programmes, but why pay artists to produce ersatz
ads for street hoardings instead of working in television? If artists must
be induced to ape advertisements why not television commercials?
Artists' Journeys look like conventional art appreciation programmes, the
quality depending largely on the charisma and articulacy of the presenter,
Avigdor Arikha being inspiring on Velasquez but Jim Dine (next Sunday)
somewhat gnomic and private on Munch.
These programmes do not look like a carefully planned season, they look like
an odd assortment shoved together under one umbrella as an afterthought in
the hope of creating extra publicity. Some are good, some are poor, and the
billboard exercise seems a questionable way to spend licence fees (assuming
that is where the money came from). Despite all that, 'Commissions And
Collaborations' contains programmes of a sort which it is difficult to
imagine will ever be produced by the sort of organisation which intends to
charge you Pounds 22 a month solely to watch soccer.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
