<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Business and the Environment: Phosphates aim for clean bill
of health
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER KNIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Phosphates, thought to be environmentally criminal ingredients in
detergents, might get a reprieve if efforts to clear their name are
successful.
Initial concern about phosphates in detergents - which act primarily as a
water softener - dates back to the late 1960s when Lake Erie in the US
'bloomed' with an unusually strong growth of algae. Detergents were blamed.
Similar blooms now occur throughout the world and are part of a process
called eutrophication (rich in nutrients). These blooms have been blamed on
unusually high amounts of phosphates getting into rivers and lakes via
sewage systems and from farms.
The algae consume the oxygen in the water and deny it to other water life,
such as fish, which then die. Sometimes the algae rot and can be poisonous
if eaten by animals.
Most 'green' detergents exclude phosphates and declare this on the label.
The phosphates are replaced with higher levels of surfactants (the cleaning
agent) or alternatives are used.
Italy and Switzerland have banned phosphates from household detergents but
the UK government has called for more research before it makes up its mind
on the subject. In Stockholm, on the other hand, city authorities encourage
citizens to use detergents that contain phosphates.
At the heart of the argument is the EC's directive on municipal wastewater
treatment which should be implemented by 1998. This stipulates that sewage
works in areas suffering from eutrophication must install strippers to
remove most of the phosphates from the treated water.
Phosphate supporters argue that detergent-based phosphates contribute only a
small amount to the total quantity of phosphates in the water supply. Most
comes from agriculture and other constituents of sewage.
Furthermore, the substance is more efficient than alternatives. Zeolite, a
substitute, tends to form a sludge which can reduce the efficiency of sewage
works. If phosphates in sewage can be removed by stripping - and possibly
re-used as a fertiliser - then it makes sense to use the substance in
detergents.
This argument is backed by evidence which shows that phosphate bans in
Switzerland and Italy have not solved those countries' eutrophication
problems. The amount of detergent used in Switzerland has increased since
the phosphate ban because householders have used more to compensate for
reduced cleaning power.
Those who argue against phosphates say the EC directive will take nearly a
decade to be implemented and then strippers will only be sited in some
areas. They point to evidence gathered by the National Rivers Authority in
the UK which identifies eutrophication as a big problem in an area of
southern England which was previously unaffected.
There is no clear winner in the argument. The UK government commissioned a
report on the issue which concluded that there was insufficient evidence to
ban phosphates. The government then consulted industry and environment
groups and found little agreement on the issue.
It commissioned more research and allowed manufacturers to continue using
phosphates.
But environment groups have, for the most part, abandoned phosphates as a
campaign issue. Most of the confrontation on the subject is now taking place
within the industry.
Last year in France, for example, Rhone-Poulenc, a chemicals group, took
Henkel to court for promoting its phosphate-free detergent, Le Chat, as good
for the environment. The court found in Rhone-Poulenc's favour and fined
Henkel FFr150,000 (Pounds 15,000) for each infringement of the judgment.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 16
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-6052</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CE0AWAEXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920527
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Scotland gains a voice of its own in Brussels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND yesterday gained representation in Brussels when Mr Ian Lang, the
Scottish secretary, launched a body designed to help Scottish organisations
and businesses make the most of the European Community.
Scotland Europa is a hybrid - neither the embassy of an independent Scotland
nor the official representative office of a European region, but a
subsidiary of Scottish Enterprise, the official development body. It is a
joint venture between the public and private sectors and is expected to pay
its way from fees and rent within three years.
Although Scotland Europa houses representatives of Scottish Enterprise, the
main job of its chief executive - Mr Grant Baird, a canny 49-year-old who
was until recently chief economist of the Royal Bank of Scotland - is to act
for the members he signs up.
They include bodies such as Glasgow Chamber of Commerce, Edinburgh
University and the Scottish Trade Union Congress, and companies, of which
the first three to sign up are ScottishPower, Scottish Hydro-Electric and
Glasgow-based BP Exploration.
The organisation is the product of several years of argument about how
Scotland should best be represented in the EC without infringing the
prerogatives of the Foreign Office and arousing the anxieties of the
Treasury about costly duplication of facilities.
About 35 European regions already have offices in Brussels to keep abreast
of developments in the EC and lobby for their interests. The most
influential are said to be those of the German Lander, which report back to
the Land governments and legislatures.
The UK government decided that Scotland could not have a regional office
because of its status as part of the UK, which is a unitary state. Germany,
on the other hand, is a federation. The Scottish Office makes its
representations in Brussels through the UK's permanent representative office
in Brussels, UKREP, which is part of the Foreign Office.
Even Mr Bruce Millan, the former Labour Scottish MP who is the EC regional
development commissioner, said yesterday that this was the right way for
Scotland to deal with the Commission. He admitted, though, that he would
personally prefer Scotland to have its own devolved parliament and thus
separate representation in Brussels.
Some observers of regional activities in Brussels have warned that Scotland
Europa, because it lacks the status of an official government body in
Brussels, will lack influence when it tries to fulfil its aim of trying to
increase the flow of EC funds to Scotland.
Yet even before the setting up of Scotland Europa, whose creation follows
hard on the heels of Brussels offices for Northern Ireland and Wales, Scots
had been effective in obtaining EC funds. Strathclyde Regional Council,
Scotland's largest local authority, has had an office in Brussels for
several years and is at present coming towards the end of implementing a
Pounds 300m programme of regional aid.
The Highlands and Islands are dotted with European flags denoting EC-funded
projects.
The idea is that as Scotland Europa gains more members - it has about 20,
with a further 10 being courted - it will become the centre of a network of
intelligence on the likely effects for Scotland of what is going on in the
Community.
Members of Scotland Europa can purchase Mr Baird's time, depending on the
level of their subscriptions, to investigate new Commission proposals and
make representations about them. He admits that his agenda will largely be
dictated by his clients rather than following a predetermined strategy.
However, in one sense there is already a network of intelligence-gathering
on Scottish interests in Brussels.
Scotland Europa is handing out a booklet with the names, positions and
telephone numbers of all Scots known to be working in the Commission and the
Belgian capital. With cheerful allusions to the Mafia, it calls the network
Scotia Nostra.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
