<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / A matter of striking a balance: The new trade minister
discusses his objectives
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL andAND RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Richard Needham, the new trade minister, is anxious to deflect criticism
of Britain's export performance. He treads a balanced path between
reassuring businessmen worried by trade deficits and avoiding overt backing
for a more interventionist government policy.
After a month in his job, the new man at the Department of Trade and
Industry (DTI) is sufficiently astute not to criticise his predecessors but
believes that in promoting UK exports there has to be a more constructive
relationship between the DTI and industrialists. It would be churlish to
make too much of the fact that his predecessors made similar noises and made
light of the steady deterioration in relations with industry.
Yesterday Mr Needham faced top exporters concerned at the lack of support
and frustrated by the government's preference for seemingly endless bright
public-relations ploys - such as last September's export initiative to
Venezuela, or the Kuwait 'task force' aimed at winning business after the
Gulf war. Exporters would rather have help on export finance or the use of
more aid funds to boost exports.
Britain's export performance is not as bad as critics claim, Mr Needham
says. The long-term decline in Britain's share of world trade has
stabilised. The UK exports the equivalent of Pounds 1,800 a person a year.
Japan manages only Pounds 1,000.
The volume of UK exports has grown significantly faster in the last year
than many other leading industrial countries. 'That gives us a base on which
we can build,' he says.
When he was Ulster's economy minister he was regarded as interventionist, a
charge he does not deny, but he rejects any suggestion that he wants a
greater injection of public money into industry, talking instead of working
in 'partnership'. While his statements suffer from cliche, he does strive to
give them substance. 'What the DTI can do . . . in many parts of the world
is to work together with industry to ensure that if there are orders out
there, that they are got by us.'
Support should not just be forthcoming in officially sponsored export drives
but also when the DTI negotiates on the General Agreement on Tariffs and
Trade, within the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development or
on the European single market, he says.
The government, he adds, should be seen to be backing winners and encourage
industry 'to feel that they have got that backing. That 'backing winners'
principle is going to be very important.'
He was unwilling to offer any pledges to increase the support that
government gives to exporters to sell goods in volatile or difficult
markets. UK industrialists complain regularly about the limited availability
of medium and long-term export-credit cover and the high cost of
export-credit insurance premiums, which they regard as unfair handicaps on
exports. Yet there is not even a hint that Mr Needham will try to meet their
complaints.
He is sympathetic, if uncompromising. 'Not everyone is going to get what
they want, but at least if you have a partnership and there is a large
degree of trust and confidence it is much easier, in those circumstances
when things don't always go right, to ride the squalls.' Such backing for
exporters extends to spending time on helping to restore the image of
industry and selling the idea of industrial benefits to young people.
'The last great exposition of British industrial might was in 1851 . . .
Ever since then, the whole atmosphere and attitude of the establishment
towards industry has declined, right through the education system, through
the Civil Service, through the professions and so on. Now I believe that
that is starting to come back.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
</DOC>
