<DOCNO>FT922-6055</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CE0AWAEUFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920527
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Needham issues pledge to exporters
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PROMISE of a fresh dialogue between the government and exporters about
how to improve the performance of British exports was made yesterday as a
six-strong delegation from the British Exporters' Association (Bexa) met Mr
Richard Needham, the trade minister.
Mr Needham agreed to meet the exporters in three months' time to update them
on what the government was doing and to hear their concerns.
The Department of Trade and Industry said the new minister found the meeting
'helpful and useful'.
Bexa said it believed that the dialogue would 'lead to a comprehensive
understanding of our mutual objectives in maintaining and developing the
international competitiveness of the UK export industry, for the overall
benefit of the country's economy'. The delegation was led by Mr Keith
Johnson, the chairman of its industry section.
The association said it had not previously had a dialogue with ministers.
Differences between exporters and the government were consistently
highlighted last year over the government's sale of the insurance services
group, the short-term credit insurance arm of the Export Credits Guarantee
Department.
More generally, exporters have expressed a view that the UK government is
not doing as much as its foreign counterparts to promote British exports.
Earlier this month, a memorandum from Bexa warning ministers of the risk
that the UK was turning into 'a screwdriver-assembly economy' was leaked to
the Labour party.
While just a general and introductory discussion, yesterday's meeting still
focused on export services provided by the government, including the role of
the continuing ECGD.
In the past few years, trade ministers have often committed themselves to
listening to, and working in partnership with, British industry, while in
practice relations have become progressively worse.
</TEXT>
