<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Old Masters hold their class: Saleroom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OLD MASTER pictures have survived the downturn in the art market better than
most sectors and both Sotheby's and Christie's held encouraging auctions in
New York at the weekend. Sotheby's was particularly cheered by a sale that
totalled Dollars 15.4m (Pounds 8.45m) with 13 per cent unsold.
The top price was Dollars 1.48m (Pounds 814,000) for a previously unknown
painting by Canaletto of Venice's Grand Canal looking south-west. To attract
bids in what is still a convalescent market, Sotheby's had put a temptingly
low estimate on the work of about Dollars 500,000.
The auction contained a group of paintings from the collection of Jaime
Ortiz-Patino including another Venetian view, of the Church of San Giorgio
Maggiore, by the other great 18th-century recorder of the city, Guardi,
which sold within forecast for Dollars 1.26m.
'A Village Wedding Dance', by Pieter Brueghel the Younger sold for Dollars
577,500 and another 'lost' painting, 'Boethius and Philosophy', by the
17th-century Italian artist Mattia Preti, which carried a Dollars 60,000
estimate, sold for Dollars 506,000. Sotheby's noticed stronger buying from
private American collectors.
All told, Sotheby's raised Dollars 29.4m for Mr Ortiz-Patino from its
auctions of furniture, silver and paintings from his collection. That
comfortably exceeded its pre-sale estimate of Dollars 22m.
Christie's main achievement in its Old Masters auction was selling all 31
paintings offloaded as surplus stock by the J. Paul Getty Museum in Malibu,
California. They totalled Dollars 3.33m. Top price in the sale was 'The
Bathers' by Francois Le Moyne, which had been estimated at Dollars 60,000
but which sold to a London dealer for Dollars 451,000.
</TEXT>
