<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Education programme at Ford improves industrial relations
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
AN EDUCATION programme at Ford has significantly improved industrial
relations at the motor company, according to senior managers and union
leaders.
Mr Jack Adams, deputy general secretary of the TGWU general union and the
senior Ford negotiator, said the Education and Development Assistance
Programme (EDAP) had been responsible for keeping last year's pay talks to
one day - the first time this had happened for many years. Last year was
also the first year in which no strike threat was made.
EDAP, in which Ford pays up to Pounds 200 a year for each employee's
after-work education, is run by local committees on which union and
management representatives have an equal say. In the magazine of the
Involvement and Participation Association, Mr Adams says union-management
co-operation on the project had caused 'suspicions on both sides to
diminish'. EDAP, which was set up in 1988, allows employees to study any
subjects except those which have a direct bearing on their jobs.
Mr John Hougham, Ford's personnel director, told the magazine: 'We have had
experience of working together, of learning together, of co-ownership, of
joint acceptance of responsibility, of actually sharing an enormous
enthusiasm for what we are achieving.'
A report by the Ruskin College Trade Union Research Unit emphasises that
EDAP has not only improved union-management relations but also the relations
between employees themselves.
It adds that the company will benefit from easier recruitment and retention
and concludes that EDAP is a model of what 'social partnership' could
achieve.
</TEXT>
