<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / DoE predicts a sharp fall in spending on training
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GOVERNMENT spending on the country's two largest training schemes
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Youth Training and Employment Training - will fall sharply in real terms in
1993-94, according to internal Department of Employment estimates.
The cut, partly for demographic reasons, is expected and follows similar
cuts over the past two years. YT is likely to be cut from Pounds 851m in
1992-93 to Pounds 845m in Pounds 1993-94 and ET, for unemployed adults, will
rise slightly in nominal terms, from Pounds 807m to Pounds 818m, but not
enough to cover inflation.
The leaders of the 104 Training and Enterprise Councils, which administer YT
and ET in England and Wales and spearhead the government's training
initiative, will try to resist the cuts in the spending discussions with the
Treasury and the Department of Employment which begin next month.
The Tecs' main priority is to win greater flexibility for the way they spend
their money. They want more money to be based on 'outputs' - the number of
people who achieve specified qualifications, or jobs - rather than 'inputs',
the number of people who start courses. People currently finishing ET
courses have little more chance of finding a job than people who do not do
ET at all.
Lord Stockton, chairman of Centec in central London and unofficial spokesman
for Tec leaders, said Tecs wanted freedom to offer ET training to people who
have been unemployed for only three months, instead of the current threshold
of six months.
Tecs also want more flexibility on the length of courses, arguing that some
people need shorter but higher-quality courses and others longer but
lower-level. 'Inflexibility has exacerbated the funding problem,' Lord
Stockton said.
Tecs are keen to divert as much money as possible from big training schemes
for the unemployed to the demanding Investors in People training standard
for people already at work. The government is also keen to push Investors in
People but will not allow Tecs to abandon the guarantee of a training place
for all people under the age of 25.
Some London Tecs have still not agreed their budgets with the Department of
Employment for the current year but are expected to do so in the next few
weeks.
</TEXT>
