<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Talks venue adds Pounds 5m to EC presidency cost
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN's six-month presidency of the European Community, starting on July
1, will cost up to Pounds 5.5m more as a result of the decision to hold the
Heads of Government summit in Edinburgh rather than in London.
The Foreign Office said yesterday that the meeting will cost Pounds 6.4
million to stage in Edinburgh, compared with an initial estimate of Pounds
900,000 for holding it in London. However, the Foreign Office added that
even had the summit stayed in the capital that figure would have been
higher.
The decision by Mr John Major, the prime minister, to hold the EC leaders'
summit in Edinburgh was taken in the run-up to the general election with the
aim of reinforcing his adherence to the Union with Scotland.
A large part of the extra cost for staging the meeting in the Scottish
capital will come from renovating Holyroodhouse, where the talks will be
held.
The cost of different locations has been taken into account by the Foreign
Office in deciding on venues for the other council meetings and informal
talks, all of which are expected to be held in London.
A further Pounds 3.4 million has been set aside to cover the costs of the
six-month presidency.
