FT  27 MAY 92 / Leader of Names attacks militants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR PETER NUTTING, a prominent Names' leader and a member of Lloyd's Council,
the insurance market's governing body, yesterday launched a ferocious attack
on more militant Names' leaders.
Mr Nutting, who earlier this year led a successful campaign for compensation
by nearly 1,000 Outhwaite Names, resigned his chairmanship of the Lloyd's
Names Association's Working Party on Friday.
He said: 'It is becoming increasingly apparent that some leaders and members
of the committees of some action groups are involved in a highly organised
and well orchestrated campaign of vilification against Lloyd's, its council
and most of those who earn their living on the market.'
Mr Nutting is particularly critical of legal efforts by Names - individuals
whose assets back underwriting - that are designed to win injunctions to
prevent Lloyd's drawing down their deposits in order to pay insurance
losses. He said such action 'strikes at the foundations of Lloyd's'.
Although UK Names have so far been unsuccessful in two separate efforts to
win injunctions, an American Name was granted an injunction by a Denver
court last week.
The Lloyd's Names Association Working party has been involved in discussions
with Lloyd's about a bail-out scheme to help Names facing severe
underwriting losses.
However, it has not been supported by the biggest Names association, the
Gooda Walker Names Action Group, which has more than 2,100 members.
The Gooda Walker Names' chairman, Mr Alfred Doll-Steinberg, is backing
another effort to win injunctions for his Names and has been critical of Mr
Nutting's more moderate approach. Mr Nutting also says that action groups
should postpone any action until the Lloyd's reviews are complete. Mr
Nutting said: 'I believe a number of action groups would be well-advised not
to confuse activity with action which is in most cases premature and in some
cases counter-productive. I strongly urge all members of action groups to
reject the leadership of extremists.'
</TEXT>
