<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Courts and cash tax limits of the power of prayer: Problems
of strategy and finance inthe Christian Science church
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHRISTIAN Science reading rooms are usually calm, quiet places befitting a
religion that emphasises the power of prayer. But beneath the surface, the
Boston-based First Church of Christ, Scientist has been riven by a debate
over strategy, finances and leadership.
At the centre of the US-based religion's problems has been an ambitious
attempt - now partly abandoned - to build a miniature media empire. The
effort, started in the 1980s, has cost dearly and dented the church's
finances. Distressed at this and the manner in which those finances were
being handled, some senior figures resigned earlier this year. They included
John Hoagland, one of the principal forces behind the media expansion, who
stepped down as one of three trustees of the Christian Science Publishing
Society.
Since then an uneasy lull has descended and the external spotlight on the
church's affairs has dimmed. But, with three events scheduled to take place
over the next month, it seems unlikely that matters will stay subdued.
For a start, lawyers will appear in a probate court today, attempting to
assert the church's right to a Dollars 98m (Pounds 55.3m) bequest against
competing claims from the Los Angeles County Museum of Art and Stanford
University.
Meanwhile, the First Church of Christ, Scientist - known to Christian
Scientists as the 'Mother Church' - is preparing a comprehensive report on
its finances. This should reach members by the annual meeting on June 8.
And there is still the vexed question of what the Christian Science movement
does with its 'Monitor Channel', the US cable operation which caused many of
its financial difficulties in the first place. A deadline of June 15 has
been set for its sale, and if a buyer cannot be found the operation will
close.
This all represents unwelcome publicity for a movement founded by Mary Baker
Eddy, then Mrs Patterson, in 1866. The 45-year-old New Englander, who lived
near Lynn in Massachusetts, suffered bad internal injuries after a fall. She
attributed her subsequent recovery to the invocation of divine power through
prayer, and spent the rest of her life spreading a gospel of Christian
healing.
The church itself was formed in 1879. However, its early years were marked
by organisational upheavals, and what emerged was a structure which differed
significantly from that of other organised forms of Christianity. Today,
most Christian Scientists have dual membership, both to a local
democratically-run 'branch' church, and to the Mother Church, governed by a
'self-perpetuating' board of directors.
The religion has long been active in the publishing world - starting with
The Christian Science Journal, which Mary Baker Eddy founded in 1883.
However, for most of this century its flagship operation has been the
Christian Science Monitor, a respected daily newspaper with strong
international coverage and a predominantly secular approach. Reputation
notwithstanding, the Monitor has been the victim of falling circulation
recently. It sells 108,000 copies a day, a third down on a decade ago.
It was in the mid-1980s that the Mother Church started to build up a broader
range of media operations. It began to produce TV and radio news programmes,
acquired a TV station in Boston, and started to transmit shortwave radio
broadcasts worldwide. The most ambitious project, however, was the Monitor
Channel, a 24-hour news and current events channel. This began to air in
early 1991 and, at one stage, employed several hundred people.
These wide-ranging media operations required substantial subsidies from the
church. Detailed estimates of the losses have varied substantially, but it
is generally acknowledged that the aggregate annual deficits ran into tens
of millions of dollars.
That, in turn, has prompted much internal debate about the expansion
strategy. Some Christian Scientists have viewed this as a justified
extension of the church's activities. Others have argued that the effort was
diverting the religion from its core principles, at worrying cost.
In the event, financial outlays and the growing dissension put an end to the
ideological debate. The church, having borrowed money from its pension fund
to back the Monitor Channel, announced on March 9 that it would shed the
operation. Today church officials say that efforts to find a buyer are
continuing and note that representatives were out in force at a big trade
show recently. However, if a new owner is not secured by June 15 they are
emphatic that the channel, already reduced to minimal technical staff, will
simply shut down.
This complex interplay of finance and ideology has not been confined to the
media expansion. Earlier this century a heavy-going book, The Destiny of the
Mother Church, was written by a Mr Bliss Knapp. Like his parents, Mr Knapp
was a prominent member of the Mother Church, and the book was published
privately in 1947. The Mother Church regarded the work as ideologically
suspect and declined to treat it as 'authorised' literature.
But, under a bequest set out before his death by Mr Knapp and his immediate
relatives, the church stood to receive millions if it reversed this policy
by 1993. Late last year it did indeed decide to make the book available in
print through the Christian Science Publishing Society. It now sells in
reading rooms for Dollars 15.
Whatever the real motivation for this change of heart, some Christian
Scientists have had misgivings, suspecting that the Mother Church was
abandoning principles for the sake of money.
In fact, the funds have not been forthcoming immediately. The two
alternative beneficiaries, the Los Angeles County Museum of Art and Stanford
University, are still seeking to determine whether the Knapp bequest
conditions have been met by the Mother Church.
And there, in uneasy fashion, matters stand. 'We put a lot of stock in the
power of prayer,' comments one church member, trying to explain that the
very secular spotlight which has been turned on the church misreads the more
spiritual approach of the membership to the church's difficulties.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
