<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Egyptians protest at Israeli air strikes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EGYPT yesterday called on the US, Russia and the United Nations to press
Israel to end the air strikes on guerrilla targets in south Lebanon which
continued yesterday and which have sharply raised tensions in the region
over the past week.
In an unusually strong statement, the Egyptian Foreign Ministry condemned
what it called Israel's 'flagrant aggression' against Lebanon and called on
it to 'desist immediately'.
It said the UN and the two sponsors of the Middle East peace negotiations -
the US and Russia - should intervene with Israel to prevent any damage to
the peace process.
Shortly after the Egyptian statement Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, the UN
secretary general, expressed concern that the escalation of violence could
jeopardise Middle East peace efforts. He deplored the loss of innocent life
and urged restraint.
Egypt, the only Arab country to have made peace with Israel, is worried that
the violence in south Lebanon could escalate out of control. Fears have been
expressed of a clash between Syria and Israel, although Israeli leaders
yesterday signalled that they did not expect such an outcome.
Israel launched repeated rocket strikes yesterday morning on positions held
by Hizbollah, the Iranian-backed Moslem fundamentalist militia fighting
Israel's occupation of a 'security zone' inside Lebanon. Four guerrillas and
one civilian were wounded.
It was the third wave of air attacks carried out by Israeli forces since a
Hizbollah force last week overran a post held by the South Lebanon Army,
Israel's surrogate militia, which polices the zone.
In one attack on a Hizbollah leader's house, his wife and two small
daughters were killed.
The attacks included strikes on positions in areas under Syrian control.
Syria was reported to have boosted its troop concentrations in Lebanon after
the attacks and its foreign minister, Mr Farouk al-Sharaa, said Syria would
have 'no option but to fight' if Israel 'imposed war'.
</TEXT>
