<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Japan tops foreign assets league: Tokyo's net overseas
holdings rise to record Dollars 383bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEFAN WAGSTYL and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN last year regained its position as the world's largest holder of net
foreign assets, despite the turmoil in Tokyo's financial markets.
Japan's net overseas assets rose 16.8 per cent to a record Dollars 383.1bn
(Pounds 216.40bn) at the end of 1991, overtaking Germany's total of Dollars
345.4bn, according to figures published yesterday by the Ministry of
Finance. Japan held the top spot for five years from 1985, before losing it
to Germany in 1990.
Economists said the figures highlighted Japan's continuing ability to invest
abroad, even though some of its financial institutions have been hit by the
slump in the Japanese stock and property markets.
The balance of Japan's gross short-term investments overseas declined
slightly - by 0.4 per cent to Dollars 759bn - because of cuts in financial
market investments by Japanese banks. Banks have been reducing foreign
assets to try to meet standards for capital adequacy set by the Bank for
International Settlements.
However, the balance of gross long-term investments rose 13.8 per cent to
Dollars 1,247.9bn, thanks to continuing investments in foreign securities,
in direct investment such as factories, and in loans made under Official
Development Aid (ODA) programmes. Taking short- and long-term investments,
Japan increased its total gross foreign assets by 8.0 per cent to Dollars
2,006.5bn.
Foreigners' investment in Japan also grew, with the balance of gross inward
investment rising 6.1 per cent to Dollars 1,623.4bn. Foreigners' long-term
investments soared 39.5 per cent to Dollars 647.4bn, as investors poured
funds into Japanese stocks and bonds, hoping to take advantage of the slump
in the Japanese equity market. Foreigners' holdings of Japanese securities
rose 32.7 per cent.
Foreigners' short-term assets declined by 8.4 per cent to Dollars 976.0bn,
as investors switched funds from short-term instruments, such as
yen-denominated bank deposits, into equities.
The disparity in flows of direct investments increased once again - with an
increase of Dollars 30.3bn, Japan's total direct investments rose to Dollars
231.8bn. Foreigners investments in Japan rose a modest Dollars 2.4bn to
Dollars 12.3bn.
Japan's June long-term prime rate has been increased by 0.3 points to 6.3
per cent, Reuter reports from Tokyo. The long-term credit banks and the
Ministry of Finance were divided over what the June long-term prime rate
should be.
Bank officials said they wanted to raise the rate by 0.3 percentage points
in line with the yield on the latest five-year bank debentures, while the
MoF said it was opposed to a 0.3 point increase on concerns about its
possible negative impact on the economy.
The increase was the first in 11 months. The rate was last raised by 0.2
points to 7.9 per cent in July 1991.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
