<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Bosnian minister campaigns for US hearts and minds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ZAGREB
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN Haris Silajdzic, the indefatigable foreign minister of
Bosnia-Hercegovina, arrived in Washington last month, he had one aim: to
jolt the US out of its indifference towards the violence and ethnic fighting
in his country.
For nearly a year, the US has relied on the European Community to shoulder
the burden of the war in the former republics of Yugoslavia. The tall and
dapper Mr Silajdzic, 47, has changed all that.
'James Baker (US secretary of state) agreed to meet Silajdzic,' a US state
department official said. 'Baker had already been briefed many times by
Larry Eagleburger, and Brent Scowcroft, both of whom were diplomats in
Belgrade in the 1960s and had close connections with Serbian President
Slobodan Milosevic. Silajdzic had a lot of work to do, a lot of records to
put straight. . . . Baker didn't know what hit him last month.'
The official said Mr Silajdzic spelt out to the secretary of state how
Serbia was trying to destabilise Bosnia's newly-won independence, and how
both Croatia and Serbia were conniving to divide Bosnia.
His sensitivity towards ethnic problems and the dangers they bring was
fostered during his university days at Pristina, the capital of the province
of Kosovo, whose ethnic Albanian majority has long been in conflict with its
Serbian overlords. Before his appointment to the foreign ministry in 1990,
Mr Silajdzic was an academic in Sarajevo. His speciality is international
relations.
'Silajdzic impressed upon Baker that this was no local war in a far away
place. He argued that the Balkans could go up in flames, involving Greece
and Turkey, two Nato allies,' another US official said.
Mr Silajdzic returned to Washington 10 days ago, with considerable
difficulty. Serb irregulars and the Yugoslav federal army have been allowing
no one in, or out of, Sarajevo airport.
Capitalising on his growing friendship with Mr Baker, the Bosnian foreign
minister then started swinging the American media behind him. His articulate
manner, helped by his impeccable English which he learned while doing a
doctorate in the US, put Bosnia-Hercegovina and its Moslems on the map.
He has also won much support among the tens of thousands of Moslem refugees
who have sought refuge in neighbouring Croatia. 'He is a kind man, and a
great man,' said Mr Shefko Cengic, a 32-year-old refugee from Sarajevo.
'Let's hope American support is backed by deeds as well.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
