FT  27 MAY 92 / France welcomes sign of recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN DAVIDSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INDICATIONS of a sharp recovery in the French economy in the first quarter
of this year have been warmly welcomed by Mr Michel Sapin, the finance
minister, who has predicted that this year's growth rate may well exceed the
2 per cent previously forecast by the government, writes Ian Davidson in
Paris.
French GDP grew by 1 per cent in the first quarter of this year, according
to official figures, and by 2.8 per cent on a year-on-year basis, twice as
fast over this period as the rest of the industrialised world.
Exports provided the main motor of the recovery, expanding by 4.3 per cent
in the first quarter or by 9.7 per cent against last year's opening period.
Household consumption has been more hesitant, with an increase of 0.7 per
cent during the quarter.
The black spot remains corporate investment, which dropped for the sixth
quarter in a row, this time by 0.6 per cent.
