<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Disposal of Mountleigh UK property may take years
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, ROBERT PESTON and PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DISPOSAL of Mountleigh's Pounds 400m UK property portfolio could take
years, according to KPMG Peat Marwick, the receiver appointed on Monday.
Mr Stephen James of KPMG said he had already received interest from
potential purchasers. But he stressed that there would be no immediate 'fire
sales'. 'It may take years to unravel,' he said.
Receivers were also appointed yesterday to 21 UK subsidiaries.
As the complexity of repaying Mountleigh's creditors became clear, bankers
warned that other property companies were likely to collapse in coming
months. 'The worst may be yet to come in the UK property market', said a
senior banker with loans outstanding to Mountleigh.
Mountleigh has two main borrowing facilities. A syndicate of nine banks,
whose agent is Barclays, has provided Pounds 329m. Also in the syndicate are
Credit Suisse of Switzerland, Citibank and Bankers Trust of the US, Unibank
of Denmark, Credit Lyonnais of France and three UK banks, Royal Bank of
Scotland, National Westminster and Lloyds.
There is a much smaller Pounds 38m syndicated loan, whose agent is Citibank.
There are also two overdraft facilities, taking Mountleigh's total bank
borrowings to more than Pounds 400m. In addition, it owes bondholders Pounds
144m.
Mr James said it would take several days to decide what should be done with
the UK property portfolio. Although the property is generally well-let, it
includes several development sites.
The largest properties in Mountleigh's UK portfolio are the Merry Hill
shopping centre at Dudley in the West Midlands, the Camberley shopping
centre in Surrey and a half share in the Criterion centre in London's
Piccadilly Circus.
The Richardson brothers, who developed Merry Hill and sold a controlling
interest in it to Mountleigh, said they might be interested in repurchasing
the shopping centre. Mr Don Richardson said: 'If we could get some
arrangement on price we couldn't let a good deal pass by.'
