<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Trade gap widest since 1990: April imports surge prompts
fears over whether recovery can be sustained
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S trade and current account deficits widened unexpectedly last
month, pointing to increased activity in the domestic economy but casting
doubts over whether the recovery can be sustained.
The visible trade deficit jumped from Pounds 891m in March to a seasonally
adjusted Pounds 1.36bn in April, the highest since August 1990.
The Central Statistical Office estimated that the deficit on current
account, which includes a projected Pounds 300m surplus from 'invisible'
trade such as services and transfers, increased last month to Pounds 1.06bn,
the biggest since January last year, from Pounds 591m in March.
Imports, when measured in volume terms and minus oil and so-called erratic
items such as aircraft, ships, oil rigs and precious stones, set a new
record in April. While some economists said the jump in imports was a
welcome sign of recovery, others expressed concern that import volumes had
already recouped the recession-linked decline before any real recovery in
the economy had become apparent.
Yesterday's figures cast some doubt on the UK's ability to maintain strong
economic growth in the medium term without experiencing the constraints of a
widening trade deficit. 'The figures bode ill for the sustainability of the
recovery,' said Mr Leo Doyle, an economist with Kleinwort Benson, the UK
merchant bank and securities group.
At the Treasury, however, a spokesman pointed out that some pick-up in
imports was to be expected as the economy recovered. He said exports were
still strong and warned that monthly trade figures could be erratic.
The April deficits were much higher than the City's consensus forecasts of
Pounds 600m for the current account and Pounds 900m for the visible trade
account. They reflected a sharp 3.5 per cent increase in the value of
imports to Pounds 10.15bn last month. Exports, at Pounds 8.79bn in April,
were 1.4 per cent lower than in March. However, exports, although down last
month, have been running at a historically high level. The volumes for both
exports and imports in the latest three months are the highest ever
recorded.
The deficits had a mixed impact on financial markets. Shares were marked
down on the news and continued lower partly because of falling prices on
Wall Street. The FTSE-100 index, up 12.1 points before the announcement,
closed at 2,704.6, down 10.4.
Sterling, protected by relatively high interest rates and membership of the
European exchange rate mechanism, shrugged off the bad news and gained
against both the D-Mark and dollar. At the London close, the Bank of
England's trade weighted sterling index was 93.1, up 0.3 on Friday's close,
while the pound closed 0.5 pfennigs higher at DM2.9425 and up 1.35 cents at
Dollars 1.828. In New York, the pound closed at Dollars 1.825 and stood at
DM2.94225 in late trading.
Details, Page 10
Needham interview, Page 10
Editorial Comment, Page 18
Lex, Page 20
Currencies, Page 31
London stocks, Page 40
