<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / London Stock Exchange: Equity Futures And Options Trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A DULL day in stock index futures saw the June contract drift lower in
afternoon trading as an aimless market looked to a weak Wall Street as its
focus, writes Christopher Price.
June opened at 2,733, and an initially lively start saw the contract
squeezed up, reaching 2,744 by 10.30am. However, this proved to be the high
point of the day, as interest drifted away. Although it still managed to
trade at a slight premium to fair value for the rest of the session, the
story was mundane as June slid with the cash market. The poor UK trade
figures added to the negative tone.
A declining Wall Street, pressured by faltering US bond prices, further
undermined June. The contract ended at 2,713, down a net 26, and around its
estimated fair value. Turnover reached 6,361 contracts. However, in
after-hours' trading, June was under further pressure, slipping to an
estimated two-point discount to fair value.
Among traded options, turnover was boosted ahead of expiry day for a number
of series. Lasmo was the top stock option, with 3,378 contracts dealt and
the August 240 series particularly busy. Hanson and Cadbury-Schweppes which
also expire today were also busy. Total turnover was 28,923 lots compared
with 26,595 on Friday.
