<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Producers plan palm oil defence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM KEELING and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JAKARTA, HAMBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INDONESIA AND Malaysia are to meet next month to discuss setting an
international standard for crude palm oil. The Philippines has also been
asked to attend the discussions, which are in response to concerns over the
high-cholesterol content of palm-oil.
An official of the Indonesian Palm Oil Producers Association said yesterday
the meeting would set a minimum standard for crude palm oil exports and was
needed 'to counter the allegation' over high cholesterol levels.
Indonesia has achieved dramatic growth in palm oil production from about
700,000 tonnes in 1980 to an estimated 2.9m tonnes last year. Exports have
risen rapidly from just 300,000 tonnes in 1980 to about 1.46m tonnes in
1990, itself a 50 per cent increase over the previous year.
A recent report by the US embassy in Jakarta estimates that 715,000 hectares
were harvested during 1990, but that a further 400,000 hectares had been
planted 'ensuring steady gains in production in coming years'. Industry
officials say a further 100,000 to 150,000 hectares is being planted every
year.
Industry officials estimate production of 3.2m tonnes this year, rising to
up to 3.7m tonnes in 1993 and 4.9m tonnes by the end of the decade.
Indonesia exports of palm oil and kernel totalled USDollars 329m last year,
up from Dollars 216m the year before. The Netherlands accounts for about
one-third of exports, while other important buyers include China, Kenya and
the UK.
Palm oil demand will exceed supply for the second consecutive season in
1991-92 (October-September), despite steadily increasing production,
according to the Oil World newsletter, reports Reuter from Hamburg.
World production is expected to rise by 740,000 tonnes to 11.94m tonnes in
1991-92 but usage will jump 1.12m tonnes to 12.33m tonnes.
</TEXT>
