<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / International Company News: Launch date for Sony's Mini Disc
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BURTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SONY, the Japanese consumer electronics group, said yesterday it planned to
introduce its Mini Disc portable player, a miniaturised version of the
compact disc, in Japan by November 1 and in main overseas markets by
Christmas.
The Mini Disc is competing against the Digital Compact Cassette (DCC) as the
next-generation recording system with the audio quality of the compact disc
(CD).
Sony, which is seeking a new popular product to reverse its fall in earnings
for fiscal 1991, hopes the Mini Disc will repeat the success of its Walkman
cassette player, with the Mini Disc replacing cassettes in the same way the
CD has succeeded the long-playing record.
The Mini Disc will be the first compact disc system able to record as well
as play. Sony said it would price the Mini Disc at Y80,000 (Dollars 617) for
a record/playback model and Y60,000 for a playback-only version.
Pre-recorded mini disc albums would cost about the same as CD albums, which
is Y2,500 in Japan, while blank discs would be about Y1,000.
Matsushita recently announced it would market its first Digital Compact
Cassette (DCC) player in Japan on September 21. The DCC table unit would be
priced at Y135,000. A portable DCC player is scheduled to be launched next
spring at a lower price. The DCC technology, which uses a cassette tape, was
developed by Philips of the Netherlands.
Analysts believe that the Mini Disc may have gained a competitive edge over
the DCC, at least in the Japanese market, because of its lower price and its
compact disc format.
'The failure of digital audio tape (Dat) indicates that consumer interest in
the use of cassette tape is waning, while the preference for compact discs
is growing,' says Mr Chuck Goto, an analyst at S. G. Warburg Securities. The
price of the Mini Disc must still fall further to penetrate the mass market,
he adds.
However, Mr Barry Dargan, deputy head of research at James Capel in Tokyo,
believes there is still consumer resistence to both the Mini Disc and DCC
systems, with the most popular alternative being a recordable standard-size
compact disc. 'The advantage with the Mini Disc is that it is at least a
step in that direction.'
Sony said it has signed licensing agreements with 22 hardware manufacturers
for Mini Disc technology. They include many of the main Japanese and Korean
consumer electronics companies. Eight companies have signed similar
agreements to produce recorded software and 10 to make blank discs.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 26
</PAGE>
