<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / International Company News: ABSA turns in earnings of R491m
in first full year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ABSA, South Africa's largest banking group, reported attributable earnings
of R491.4m (Dollars 174m) in the year to March, the first full year of the
group's existence.
ABSA was formed in early 1991 from the merger of the United Building
Society, Allied, Volkskas and part of the Sage group. A further merger,
early in 1992, with the Bankorp group, confirmed ABSA's status as South
Africa's largest banking group in terms of assets.
The effects of this second merger, which is still being carried out, are not
reflected in the current results. The timing of the first merger invalidates
comparison with earlier results.
The net interest margin was R2.3bn, but set against this was a very large
provision of R451m for bad and doubtful debts. Other operating income was
R974.5m, leaving total operating income of R2.85bn. Operating expenditure
was R2.2bn.
Total assets of ABSA rose by 8.5 per cent to R56.2m - in line with the
industry, but a 6 per cent drop in real terms.
Mortgage loans represent 33 per cent of total assets, reflecting United and
Allied's roots as building societies. Total advances in the group came to
R42bn.
Commenting on the rationalisation, Mr Herc Hefer, chairman, said the group
had exceeded expectations by achieving net cost savings of R98m. These arose
mainly from the integration of the support services of Allied, United and
Volkskas.
There were three main phases to the rationalisation which included
consolidating the group's insurance interests and related financial
services, and integrating support and technical services.
Mr Piet Badenhorst, chief executive, said the bad debt figure reflected the
fact that the level of provisions in the group had been upgraded to the
standard maintained at United. Slightly more than half of the provisions
relate to Volkskas.
He said the group's exposure to the agricultural sector - currently in the
grips of a severe drought - was in line with that of its competitors.
Earnings per share rose by 15.2 per cent to 107.6 cents and the dividend was
lifted to 39.5 cents from 36 cents.
The policy is that the dividend cover, now up to 2.7, should reach 3.
Mr Hefer said despite the poor operating climate, further rationalisation
savings should help lift profits in the coming year.
</TEXT>
