<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / International Company News: Bouygues to raise fresh capital
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BOUYGUES, one of the world's largest construction groups, is to raise
FFr1.04bn (Dollars 180m) of new equity capital, the first leading French
quoted company to launch a big rights issue in the present stock market
rally.
The group is to issue 1.712m new shares at FFr610 each, a 5.4 per cent
discount to yesterday's opening price, to help 'pursue the development of
its mainstream activities and its diversification in France and abroad,'
said Bouygues.
It was interested in buying parts - but not all - of Elbo, the east German
construction group being privatised, said Mr Martin Bouygues, chairman. He
predicted the group's profits would rise this year from last year's FFr635m
net on turnover of around FFr64bn, about the same as in 1991.
Stockmarket analysts had expected Bouygues to take advantage of the recent
strength of its share price, up by 20 per cent from mid-February, the start
of the stock market rally, to a peak of FFr675 in mid-May. However, the
share price fell FFr19 to FFr626 by yesterday afternoon, on fears that the
rights issue would dilute earnings per share.
Other leading French groups will soon follow Bouygues' example while share
prices continue their strength, said Mr David Harrington, research analyst
at James Capel in Paris.
Bouygues has not had a rights issue for six years and was thought
undercapitalised in relation to total assets. Its debts stood at an
estimated 46 per cent of shareholders' funds at the end of last year.
Nearly three quarters of the issue, FFr744.2m, will be reserved for French
shareholders, with the remainder for international investors. Subscriptions
will be open from May 28 to June 16.
Alcatel Cable has already said it is planning to raise up to FFr1.5bn next
month. Others thought likely to benefit from an injection of fresh equity
capital include Michelin, the indebted tyre maker, Moulinex, the household
appliance group, and Ciments Francais, the construction materials supplier.
</TEXT>
