<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / International Company News: Canadian bank lifts provisions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BANK OF Nova Scotia has boosted its fiscal 1992 loan loss provisions by
CDollars 200m (USDollars 168m) or 45 per cent, to reflect its exposure to
Olympia &amp; York and other troubled borrowers.
The bank, Canada's fourth biggest, nonetheless reported a small increase in
second-quarter earnings, with the extra write down exactly offset by a
recovery in third world loans. As a result, the second-quarter provision of
CDollars 110m is unchanged from the previous three months. The provision in
the second quarter of 1991 was CDollars 85m.
Although they are among O&amp;Y's biggest lenders, the Canadian banks are
generally well-equipped to absorb substantial losses. BNS for instance,
reported that its risk-weighted capital-to-assets ratio improved in the
second quarter to 8.6 per cent from 8.3 per cent a year earlier.
Net earnings rose to CDollars 171m, or 75 cents a share, in the three months
to April 30, from CDollars 163.3m, or 73 cents, a year earlier. The
improvement was largely due to wider margins as both domestic and foreign
interest rates continued to decline. Return on equity slipped, however, to
16 per cent from 17.6 per cent.
BNS disclosed earlier that its total exposure to O&amp;Y is CDollars 600m. But
with the loans largely secured by prime office buildings and marketable
securities, the bank said that it expects 'substantial recoveries'.
Total non-performing loans, net of provisions, rose to CDollars 1.87bn on
April 30 from CDollars 1.74bn three months earlier.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 25
</PAGE>
