<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / UK Company News: The Battle For Midland - Chairman defends
Hongkong Bank's management record
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON HOLBERTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR WILLIAM Purves, chairman of HSBC Holdings, yesterday defended Hongkong
Bank's record and ability to manage a global bank and told shareholders that
the planned merger with Midland Bank was in Hong Kong and China's best
interest as well as theirs.
Speaking at the bank's annual meeting Mr Purves said the merger with Midland
would create an international banking group that would be exceptionally well
capitalised. Shareholders would be able to participate in a growing
international group with considerable potential, he said.
Hongkong Bank's planned acquisition of Midland has not found favour among
Hong Kong investors. Many have criticised the plan to create a global bank,
saying the experience of the 1980s has underlined the difficulties of such a
strategy.
But Mr Purves responded to these criticisms yesterday and said Hongkong Bank
had long experience in managing operations that span the globe.
What it envisages with the merger with Midland 'is materially different from
other attempts to establish global banks.'
'Our approach is different because our organisation has always been built on
a series of separate franchises in a variety of countries.
'What links these franchises is our commitment to international banking  -
and our highly efficient technology through which we deliver competitive
products.'
Meanwhile, the bank said that Lloyds Bank's complaint to the US Federal
Reserve over Hongkong Bank's request for a 'fast track' approval of its
acquisition of Midland was 'yet another spoiling tactic'. It was the third
letter on this issue that Lloyds had sent the Fed, it said.
The bank would be writing to the Fed in due course pointing out that the
merger did not involve the acquisition of significant banking assets in the
US. It will also cite the Fed's quick approval of Deutsche Bank's purchase
of Morgan Grenfell as precedent for a timely determination.
In a separate announcement yesterday Hongkong Bank revealed its
long-foreshadowed board restructuring. It has moved to a two-tier structure
with HSBC Holdings overseeing the bank's global operations and the separate,
overlapping, board for Hongkong Bank focusing on the bank's interest
primarily in the colony.
Among new significant appointments is Baroness Lydia Dunne's elevation to
non-executive chairman of HSBC. Lady Dunne is an executive director of Swire
and also on the board of Volvo.
Mr Victor Li, the 27-year-old son of magnate Mr Li Ka-shing, has joined the
board of Hongkong Bank following his father's recent departure.
</TEXT>
