<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / UK Company News: Merry Hill interests the Richardsons -
Mountleigh shopping centre may revert to former majority owners
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DON AND Roy Richardson, the twins who developed the Merry Hill shopping
centre and sold a controlling interest in it to Mountleigh, could again
emerge as the majority owners.
'If we could get some arrangement on price we couldn't let a good deal pass
by,' Mr Don Richardson said yesterday, contemplating the implications of
Mountleigh's collapse and anticipating that the receiver, at some stage,
will sell off Mountleigh's interest.
The Richardsons do not expect the receiver to dispose of the centre, the
jewel in Mountleigh's somewhat tarnished UK property crown, at firesale
prices. 'If he did, we'd be the first there,' Mr Richardson observed.
The attraction - at a price - for the Richardsons is clear. Rents are higher
than when they sold it, the capital value undoubtedly less. About 25m
shoppers a year visit Merry Hill, near Dudley - indeed, it was packed
yesterday. After the MetroCentre in Gateshead, it is the second largest
shopping centre in Europe.
But the ownership of the Merry Hill shopping centre, itself part of a wider
development under construction in an enterprise zone since 1982 and
involving also offices and an industrial park, is complex. The adjacent
developments are largely owned by the Richardsons. The shopping centre
ownership, however, can be split at least five ways.
The first point is that the Richardsons still have a direct interest, the
exact extent of which they have not and will not disclose.
The second is that when the Richardsons, in December 1990, sold Mountleigh
an interest for a sum which, again, they would not disclose, but which
Mountleigh latterly valued at Pounds 160m, the payments were staged. Some
payments remain outstanding, but they are secured against part of the
property. Had Mountleigh managed to sell its interest to Hammerson, the UK
property group, and O'Connor Group of the US, earlier this year, at least
some of the takings would have found their way to the Richardsons.
The third facet of the ownership is the existence of the Richmount Laser
Trust, set up by Mountleigh and the Richardsons, to attract private
investors seeking tax shelters through the purchase of a property in an
enterprise zone. Part of the Merry Hill shopping centre is owned by the
Trust.
Fourth, during the years of the centre's development - over four years to
the completion of the last and biggest phase in 1990 - a series of
individual transactions were completed with the retailers. Some own their
freehold. Others are on leases of 99 and 999 years. Others again have
shorter leases: the terms of some of them are related to turnover.
The fifth slice of ownership is that of Mountleigh. It is estimated that of
the whole it is probably about 80 per cent. But that is not to say it owns
80 per cent of all the 260 shops on the 1.85m sq ft of retailing space at
the centre. While it might own the building, the retailer may have spent
twice the value of the building's shell on the interior.
Given the fragmentation of the ownership and the presence of the Richardsons
in the background, the sale of the Mountleigh interest in Merry Hill is
likely to be a lengthy affair. It is likely to be made more complicated by
fears that it might be on contaminated land, one of the reasons given for
the collapse of the Hammerson-O'Connor purchase.
The shopping centre is on the site of old railway sidings, next door to the
old Round Oak steelworks, which closed in 1984. The Richardsons are building
an office complex next door to the shopping centre on the Round Oak site.
But the land has not been designated by anybody as contaminated and the
Contaminated Land Register in which it was feared that it might appear does
not yet exist.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 23
</PAGE>
