<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / UK Company News: British Gas silent on hive off speculation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH GAS yesterday refused to confirm or deny speculation that the
company might hive off its regional businesses or float its exploration and
production business. The reports helped the shares gain 6 1/2 p yesterday to
257p.
The group announced in January that it was undertaking a fundamental review
of its operations, following continued pressure from Ofgas, the industry
regulator and the Office of Fair Trading to introduce more competition into
the gas market.
Analysts suggested that it might be more sensible to sell off its supply
businesses in advance of increased competition in the market, and allow
shareholders to benefit, than simply to wait for its market share to be
eroded. Another option would be to float the company's Pounds 4bn
exploration and production arm.
Speculation that British Gas might be considering such a move emerged again
this weekend following the publication of an interview with Mr Cedric Brown,
senior managing director at British Gas, despite Mr Brown's refusal to
comment. Mr Brown has been tipped to become chief executive, if that role is
relinquished by Mr Robert Evans, currently both chairman and chief
executive.
Mr Steve Turner, industry analyst at Smith New Court, and one of those who
has suggested that a break-up would be in British Gas's best interests, said
he believed such speculation was premature.
'British Gas faces the task of hiving off its pipeline business before the
end of the year. It would be irresponsible for the company to undertake
major restructuring before that has been achieved, and until the regulatory
debate about returns on the pipeline business has been settled.'
</TEXT>
