<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Frank words from French entrepreneur: Jean-Luc Lagardere of
Hachette and Matra talks to William Dawkins
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Jean-Luc Lagardere's image as one of France's top self-made men has recently
taken a knock, but he is as resilient as ever and swears his strategy
remains valid.
Mr Lagardere almost takes relish in countering the widespread criticism of
his latest scheme, which he argues has been poorly understood since being
unveiled earlier this month.
Unkind spirits have condemned the merger of the two companies he controls -
Matra, the transport, telecommunications and defence group, with Hachette,
France's leading international publisher - as panic.
Some see it as a way to use profitable Matra to pay for the FFr3.55bn
(Pounds 359.7m) losses clocked up by La Cinq, the now defunct television
station which Mr Lagardere bought for Hachette 18 months ago. The
64-year-old Mr Lagardere recognises this as the most serious setback in his
career.
Others see it as an eccentric attempt to find common interests between
unrelated businesses or a cynical attempt to fend off possible bids. Mr
Lagardere forcefully denies these claims.
'People take me for either an idiot or a hooligan. I believe I am neither
one nor the other,' he says. 'You don't tie someone with a broken leg to a
healthy person and expect them to go faster . . . I won't tell you that
there is a synergy between magazines and missiles . . . but that's not the
point.'
So what is the point? The big advantage of the merger is that it will allow
both sides to draw cashflow centrally for investments in each of the nine
activities in which they are jointly present, he says. There will be big
head office and administrative savings, but that is a secondary gain.
The project is in line with his mostly successful business strategy, Mr
Lagardere insists. He has always believed that any business that cannot
guarantee very high sales volumes must diversify to survive.
It must be ready to adapt, to take risks, close lossmakers when the risks
get too great, seek partners where it can no longer compete alone  - as
Matra is doing in telecommunications - and move into new areas. The merger
will help both groups by making them financially stronger and more flexible,
he argues.
'I have always been convinced that one cannot make a group live eternally on
a single product. You need an enormous effect of mass to do that . . . Look
at Dassault,' he says, referring to the aircraft group where he trained as a
designer of prototypes in the 1950s. 'Nobody could have succeeded better at
what they are doing, and yet they have not sold a single military aircraft
outside France for the past four years.'
Mr Lagardere's Dassault years marked him in all kinds of ways. His
engineering roots are evident in the way he sketches graphs to illustrate
his points. The experience also bought him into close contact with Matra,
then a single product company supplying missiles to Dassault, now much more
diversified with innovations including the Espace family and the VAL
automatic metro.
Matra's controlling shareholder invited him to take over as managing
director at the age of 34, which Mr Lagardere did on condition that he got
carte blanche. The same shareholder supported Mr Lagardere's takeover of
Hachette in 1980.
From the start, Mr Lagardere has been driven by two main impulses. First,
the urge to create a great company, which he attributes to a passion to
redress France's wartime humiliation; and second, the realisation that as an
entrepreneur he must take investment risks, but cut his losses if the
company's life is threatened. Clearly, he argues, multi-product companies
can spread risks more easily.
'When we took over La Cinq, it was losing money, but I reckoned that these
were not losses but investments. I have always said that once an investment
becomes a loss, it is time to cut. If I had continued with La Cinq in 1992,
the fatal risk for the group would have been real.' He points out that
Hachette will be easily recapitalised before the merger with Matra, so there
is no question of robbing the electronics group to bail out Hachette.
Neither was there any question of hoping that the French state would bail
out the television station. Mr Lagardere has always taken pride in belonging
to none of the political or financial power networks that bind corporate
France together. So he could expect no special favours. 'I have never
stepped into that world, never. I have always known how to work with the
establishment, but I keep my distance,' he says.
In other countries, a La Cinq-type disaster might have provoked the
resignation of the chairman. Yet Mr Lagardere has, if anything, strengthened
his position by putting the new merged group under the control of a societe
en commandite par actions, a share partnership in which the partners, headed
by Mr Lagardere, have unlimited personal liability for losses but are almost
unsackable. 'On the subject of resignation, even in England it's not so
simple . . . I used to have a motor racing team with Jackie Stewart as
driver. It happened that one day he lost a Grand Prix. But we didn't replace
him at the next race because he had won 10 previously.'
If chairmen were sacked every time they made a mistake, 'business would
become a game of massacre, in which those who succeeded would be the ones
who did nothing. My idea of business is that one must dare to take risks,'
he says. Mr Lagardere dislikes pressure for short-term performance,
something which he could produce by selling assets. 'Unlike some people who
I will not name, that is not my idea of entrepreneurship,' he says.
Suggestions that the commandite structure artificially protects management
overlook the fact that the partners' personal liabilities are very real, he
argues.
'For me, it is a profession of faith to make money and to stay independent .
. . Institutional shareholders should say to themselves that Lagardere is
obliged to make money, for all his personal fortune is in it. Unless he is
mad or a masochist, he must make money.'
Whether or not you believe his strategy of pooling his businesses to give
them the strength to diversify, Mr Lagardere is and will remain a driven
man.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
