<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Oil groups may form mutual insurer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SEDGWICK, the insurance broker, and Price Waterhouse, the accountants and
management consultants, are joining forces in a bid to help leading European
oil and gas companies form a new mutual insurance company.
The new mutual, which could have a capital base of more than Dollars 50m
(Pounds 28m) and a minimum of 15 members, would provide extra insurance
capacity in the specialist energy insurance market, where rates have
increased and capacity diminished following recent losses.
Since December, both Sedgwick and Price Waterhouse have conducted
feasibility studies and intend to hold more detailed discussions with their
clients within the next two weeks.
No company has yet agreed to join the proposed mutual, but both
organisations report a general feeling of support from their clients for the
concept.
'We believe the support is there. We are literally having clients say to us
'when can we have it?',' said Mr Chris Mundy, director of marketing at
Sedgwick Energy, the broker's specialist subsidiary.
'We would like to think we would be putting together a cast-iron proposal
within the next four to six weeks,' added Mr Mundy, who said that there was
an urgent need for action because of the contraction in available capacity.
Sedgwick's 200 clients include British Petroleum, Shell, Amerada Hess and
Mobil.
A number of oil majors which have North American interests are already part
of a mutual company, Oil Insurance Ltd (OIL), which was formed in the late
1960s.
Mr Richard Titley, chairman of Sedgwick Energy, said the new mutual would
'complement OIL by focusing on European assets.' Hit by losses such as the
explosion of the Piper Alpha rig in the North Sea in July 1988, specialist
energy insurers, including Lloyd's syndicates, have increased rates and
reduced the amount of cover available.
Oil companies, especially those in the North Sea, have massive insurance
exposures, sometimes in excess of Dollars 2bn.
Last year buyers faced rate increases of between 15 and 200 per cent, and
Sedgwick expects the tightness in the market to continue. 'Capacity is going
to be diminished,' added Mr Titley.
</TEXT>
