<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / EC weakens environment plans ahead of Earth Summit in Rio
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Community's position at next week's Earth Summit in Rio de
Janeiro looks set to fall well short of what environment commissioner Carlo
Ripa di Meana has proposed, and his own attendance at the summit was last
night in doubt.
Environment ministers of the 12 yesterday agreed to sign the Climate Change
convention due to be agreed in Rio.
But they did not agree to endorse politically the European Commission's plan
to tax energy as a means of curbing carbon dioxide emissions, even though no
EC state opposed the proposal.
Nor were they able to agree on a timetable for nearly doubling development
aid to a minimum of 0.7 per cent of gross domestic product to help
developing countries adopt more environmentally sound development
strategies.
Taken together, this is a limp posture when set against what Mr Ripa de
Meana had defined as the minimum 'dowry' the Community should take to Rio.
The Commission's plan is to stabilise CO emissions at 1990 levels by 2000,
through an energy tax equivalent to Dollars 10 a barrel of oil equivalent.
Mr Ripa di Meana says the EC can only deliver half that target without a
tax.
The plan won strong support yesterday from Germany, Denmark, the
Netherlands, Luxembourg and Italy. The first four attacked the Commission
for making introduction of the tax conditional on the US and Japan adopting
similar measures.
Spain, Portugal and Greece insisted that conditionality was vital to protect
EC industry.
France and the UK reserved their position behind procedure, since the
Commission overshot its deadline in producing the detailed draft directive,
which it will look at today.
'The UK position remains that when we see it, we will study it in detail,'
Mr Michael Howard, UK environment secretary, said of the tax plan.
</TEXT>
