<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Letter: Fund's financing too low fully to realise east
Europe objectives
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr ROGER GARSIDE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, As Mr John Major, the UK prime minister, visits Czechoslovakia, Hungary
and Poland this week, he may see something of what Britain is doing, through
the Know-how Fund, to help build institutions at the heart of their
economies. Because the transformation of these countries entails massive
disruption, the strength of these fledgling institutions will be severely
tried in the years ahead. If they do not stand the strain, the consequences
will not be limited to central Europe.
In all three countries, the Know-how Fund has been so successful in
attracting good projects and so quick in approving them that its budget is
stretched to its limit and, in one case, beyond that limit. This is a
tribute to a good concept, well administered. But justified pride should not
mask the fact that the present level of financing is too low.
When Mr Major speaks to his hosts of political co-operation between their
governments and the EC, his words will ring hollow if he cannot assure them
that the Know-how Fund will be increased to a level commensurate with the
economic risks to their political stability and our responsibilities as a
nation that did so much to inspire the reforms they have undertaken.
Roger Garside,
Garside, Miller &amp; Associates,
City Business Centre,
2 London Wall Buildings,
London Wall, London EC2
</TEXT>
