FT  27 MAY 92 / Letter: Automatic not for the sensible ecologist
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr ARCHIE KIDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Having commendably recommended diesel engined cars because of their
higher fuel efficiency ('Motoring: Diesels for sensible ecologists', May
23), Stuart Marshall's assertion that a car with automatic transmission 'is
ideal for the 1990s' is a complete contradiction of what a 'sensible
ecologist' should go for.
It has long been known that automatic transmission consumes 7 to 8 per cent
more power than a car with manual exchange. Unless there is some health or
medical reason for saving the driver the minute effort of using a gear
lever, surely the great majority of drivers at all interested in saving the
environment from unnecessary pollution and in minimising consumption of
irreplaceable fuel should avoid this expensive and unnecessary luxury.
Using, say, a pint of fuel per hour to obviate such a very slight personal
effort seems to me to be nothing short of an ecological crime.
Archie Kidd,
Archie Kidd (Thermal),
Seend,
Melksham,
Wiltshire SN12 6NX
</TEXT>
