<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Foreign Affairs: Bosnia's tragic example - Security
arrangements in Europe underpin renewed international interest in
Yugoslavia's civil war
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD MORTIMER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
You might think, from public statements made in the past two days by
American and European statesmen, that their top priority was doing something
effective to halt the fighting in Bosnia-Hercegovina.
Speaking in Lisbon on Sunday, Mr James Baker, the US secretary of state, was
eloquent on the subject: 'There are 35,000 diabetics now who have no
insulin. There are 6,000 women and babies who have no medicine, baby formula
or milk . . . Anyone who is looking for a reason not to act, or arguing
somehow that action in the face of this kind of nightmare is not warranted
at this time . . . is on the wrong wavelength.' This from a man who
stalwartly refused to contemplate any kind of sanctions against Iraq before
August 2 1990, in spite of evidence that Saddam Hussein was guilty of
chemical warfare and other gross violations of human rights; a man famous
for staying all of seven minutes in south-eastern Turkey in April 1991, when
it was flooded with Kurdish refugees.
By Monday, Mr John Major had taken up the theme, calling on the EC to take
measures against Serbia well beyond a token protest. Meanwhile, the
Portuguese foreign minister had promised that the EC would 'not allow those
responsible for the bloodshed to go unpunished', and Mr Klaus Kinkel, the
new German foreign minister, dotted the i: 'It must be said clearly who is
responsible. The Serbians are responsible.'
No doubt that is true. Reporters on the spot are certain that Serbian
militias in Bosnia are working in tight collusion both with Serbia itself
and with the Yugoslav army, to achieve exclusive Serb control of about
two-thirds of the republic's territory and expel the other ethnic
communities.
'Ethnic cleansing' is the euphemism for this procedure, which has been
applied also in the Serb-controlled areas of Croatia, and to a smaller
extent by the Croats in areas that they control. But of course it was not
invented by either Serbs or Croats. The Armenians are doing the same in
Nagorno-Karabakh. The Turks did it in northern Cyprus. The Israelis did it
in parts of Palestine in 1948, and again on a smaller scale in 1967. The
Czechs did it in the Sudetenland, the Poles in Silesia, Pomerania and East
Prussia, after 1945. Greeks and Turks did it to each other in 1922-3. Ever
since ethnicity began to be invoked as a basis of statehood, people trying
to build or preserve states in disputed areas have been tempted, as a last
resort, to clear those areas by force of people whose ethnic identity
renders their loyalty suspect.
Mr Baker and his European 'allies' are right to be horrified, but it is
doubtful whether any of them really believe they can stop it. 'We are really
talking about the need - maybe - to do something next time,' says an unnamed
US official quoted in the international press. 'Everyone in the loop
concedes that Yugoslavia is a past case already.'
It is an unworthy thought, but difficult to resist once it has occurred to
you, that the argument is not really about what should be done in the former
Yugoslavia but about future security arrangements in Europe. It was perhaps
no coincidence that this heightened awareness of the horrors of war in
Yugoslavia hit the headlines on the very day that France and Germany agreed
to push ahead with their proposal for a 35,000-man joint army corps,
intended to be the nucleus of a future European army.
It was last Friday, remember, that President Francois Mitterrand and
Chancellor Helmut Kohl made their announcement in La Rochelle, and it was
that very night that Mr Baker, after conferring with Mr Major, suddenly
called on 'the civilised world' to start thinking about political,
diplomatic and economic action against Serbia, and then added: 'If measures
in those fields should fail, then and only then it would be my view to take
a look at questions involving military matters.'
The beauty of this formulation is that it raises the possibility of military
action only when other measures have been tried and failed. By then, of
course, the Serbs would have more or less completed their 'ethnic
cleansing', and might even value the arrival of a 'peacekeeping force' which
would make it more difficult for armed Croats or Moslems to infiltrate the
'cleansed' area. The Turks have found a UN force very useful for that
purpose in Cyprus, and it was clearly in that spirit that the Serbs agreed
to have one in Croatia - although they are now in trouble with the UN for
trying to finish off the 'cleansing' operation after the UN troops arrived.
To be really cynical, one could argue that the prevention of ethnic
cleansing is a task unachievable by any military intervention short of a
full-scale occupation and administration, but that ethnic cleansing itself
is a useful, perhaps even essential, precondition for a successful
'peacekeeping' operation, which classically involves the interposition of a
neutral force along a clear line of demarcation between two sides.
Now think back to last summer, when the fighting in Yugoslavia started.
Victory in the Gulf War had reasserted the US's military supremacy and
indispensability, but the Europeans, aided by US public opinion, had bounced
President Bush into intervening in Kurdistan, from which he was trying to
extricate his troops as fast as possible. Meanwhile the Europeans were
wrangling among themselves and with their Nato allies about the
institutional framework for closer European defence cooperation: should it
come under Nato or should it be an aspect of the new European Union? In
other words, should America have a say in it or not?
Yugoslavia was no longer a stake in the cold war, and the US concluded it
was an area of limited strategic interest, where involvement carried
significant risks but offered few worthwhile benefits. The Europeans were
proclaiming a new 'common foreign and security policy'. Let them try their
luck.
The Europeans tried, with the results we now see. Meanwhile a compromise was
reached, at the Nato summit in Rome last November and then at Maastricht in
December, on European defence: it would be done through the Western European
Union (WEU), which was to be both 'an integral part of the development of
the European Union', and 'a means to strengthen the European pillar of the
Atlantic Alliance' - the latter remaining 'the essential forum for
consultation among its members'.
Although the French and German governments insist that their joint corps,
which other WEU members are invited to join, will 'contribute to the
reinforcement of the Atlantic alliance,' it is clearly regarded by the US,
and by the British and Dutch, as a breach of the spirit of last year's
compromise.
That is why it is such a good moment for the US to rub Europe's nose in the
reality of its political incompetence and military irrelevance, by drawing
attention to a crisis it has conspicuously failed to solve, and by hinting
at a military intervention which, without Nato's help, it would be quite
unable to organize.
Yet I wonder if it is a wise thing to do. When Europeans have had time to
think about it, they may decide to take the task of building a force which
would be less dependent on the US more seriously.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
