<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Letter: London as financial centre of EC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr EDWARD DE BONO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, If London is to have any hope of becoming the EC financial centre there
is no more than a four-week window of opportunity to clear up the Lloyd's
mess. The Council of Lloyd's is caught in a cruel dilemma. If the LMX spiral
practices are legal and defended as such then the effect will be even more
disastrous than if they are declared illegal.
The sheer inequity of this practice will soon be obvious to all. It cannot
be kept hidden that the LMX 'pyramid' process is flagrantly to the benefit
of the brokers (and Lloyd's indirectly) at the expense of the Names.
Condoning this practice, even if legal, will mean that the traditions of the
City of London render it unacceptable as a financial centre because
exploitation is not sufficiently ruled out.
It is also very likely that the 1982 Lloyd's Act will be challenged in the
European Courts of Justice as being contrary to basic human rights. To
expect Lloyd's to regulate itself is like asking turkeys to regulate
Christmas. The case will be an acute embarrassment to the government, which
will be put in the impossible position of having to condone dubious
practices. At this point it will become obvious that London is not fit to be
the financial centre of Europe. Allowing turkeys to behave as ostriches will
not solve the dilemma. It may just not be too late for resolute action by
the government. Inquiries that are too late in reporting are not sufficient
resolute action.
Edward de Bono,
L2 Albany,
Piccadilly,
London W1V 9RR
</TEXT>
