<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Leading Article: Mr Lamont's objective
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RE-ELECTION of the Conservatives did not resolve the dilemmas of British
economic policy. It merely changed the time horizon. The government is now
able to take a strategic perspective. Such a perspective would be
unnecessary if there were no choices left to make. But there are a few, even
if the unmentionables - leaving the ERM or a realignment of sterling - are
ignored. With sterling in the wide bands, the government can vary interest
rates a little and public spending and taxation rather more. The question is
what to do with its freedom.
The chancellor of the exchequer has given his answer. He told the annual
dinner of the Confederation of British Industry last week that Britain
should aim to match Japan's inflation performance, which is about 2 per
cent, if it wants to be 'a first-rank commercial power'. This sounds very
attractive. But one might ask whether a current account deficit of Pounds
3.2bn in the first four months of 1992, for much of which the economy was in
the seventh successive quarter of decline, is consistent with being a
'first-rank commercial power'.
The official view is that the external position of a country is of no
significance. Since the authorities also argued that the monetary expansion
between 1986 and 1988 was a private phenomenon of limited policy concern,
this view is not convincing. A 'first rate commercial power' in recession,
but with a current account deficit, probably needs a real exchange rate
depreciation. With realignments ruled out, low inflation is the sole route
to that goal. Mr Lamont's target for inflation is not mere hubris. It is a
goal that must be achieved, the sooner the better.
Necessary pain
This suggests that the high interest rates of today, not to mention efforts
to put public spending back under control, represent necessary pain. So
should Mr Lamont whisper sotto voce thanks for the monetary consequences of
German unification and watch as British inflation - now merely back to where
it was before the Lawson boom - is slowly dragged down to respectable
levels? After all, under today's 5 per cent underlying rate of inflation,
sterling would lose three quarters of its purchasing power in 30 years. This
is not respectable.
His choice is not so simple. What has made the disinflationary process
effective is also what makes it so dangerous: the consequences of high
interest rates on an economy whose banks, property companies and households
took a huge bet on inflation not so many years ago. Mountleigh is the
latest, but certainly not the last casualty from that period.
Debt deflation
There is only one answer to debt deflation: low short term interest rates,
the answer supplied by the Federal Reserve in the US. But the sluggish US
recovery suggests that a powerful debt deflation can only be overcome by a
far more aggressive central bank than anything on offer in the UK.
So what should the government choose: as much monetary restraint as
possible, to get inflation down, or as little as possible, to get the
economy moving again?
Lower interest rates do appear desirable. Disinflation is in train, whatever
happens to interest rates in the short to medium term. Maybe interest rates
can even fall a sliver below German levels, which are themselves unlikely to
fall for quite a while. High German interest rates do at least virtually
guarantee that the loosening in the UK will not be overdone.
Yet whatever the government now chooses, the legacy it inherits from its own
and its predecessor's errors ensures that the outcome will be unhappy:
underlying inflation will not fall as fast as the government hopes; recovery
will not be as strong as it might wish. More important still, even when
underlying inflation has at last been driven down to low levels, strong
growth may well not ensue.
Like the British public, the government has taken a gamble. The public bet
on inflation. The government has bet on the ERM. It has bet that the weak
balance of payments position will not constrain future growth; it has bet as
well that a heavily indebted economy will return to health despite high real
interest rates. Only time will tell whether the gamble will work. Even a
newly re-elected government can only do a little more than hope.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
