<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / The Week In Luxembourg: Milking the Community cow - European
Court
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRICK COURT CHAMBERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Dairy farmers who were paid a premium by the European Community to take a
five-year holiday from milk production are entitled to damages for lost
income they would have received during the period under the EC additional
milk levy quota, the European Court of Justice (ECJ) ruled last week.
The Court said the Community must compensate the farmers because they had
accepted a temporary EC non-marketing premium for a period chosen by Dutch
and German authorities under 1984 EC milk rules which the ECJ had already
ruled invalid because they breach Community law on protection of legitimate
expectations.
The ECJ held that the Community had incurred liability because of its
failure to take account of the specific situation of the producers affected
without invoking any higher public interest.
The extent of damage to be compensated was the loss of income that would
otherwise have been earned. Income earned from alternative occupations had
to be deducted in mitigation. Interest was awarded at the rate claimed but
at a maximum of 8 per cent.
The farmers were not entitled to further damages under a 1989 amendment to
the milk rules which allowed producers a provisional quota. Although the
1989 amendment was equally invalid, the breach of EC law on protection of
legitimate expectations was not sufficiently serious to entitle them to
compensation because the Community legislature had considered all relevant
interests in making its legitimate economic policy choice.
All dairy farmers in the same situation as those in last week's test cases
will be entitled to claim damages caused by invalid EC rules on the
additional milk levy quota introduced in 1984, but not for any loss caused
by the failure of the 1989 rules to allocate sufficient quota.
However, those involved have as much as a year to agree the calculation of
the amount of damages, in accordance with principles laid down by the Court.
So while final adjudication in the event of disagreement is reserved to the
Court, further delay and complications are likely before any dairy farmers
are compensated.
Mulder and others v Council and Commission, Joined Cases C-104/89 and
C-37/90, FC, 19 May 1992.
Last Friday, ECJ president Ole Due refused the European Commission's
application for interim measures against the UK in a case concerning the
scope of the monopoly enjoyed under EC law by the five UK Milk Marketing
Boards (MMBs) over 'milk produced and marketed without processing'.
The UK says the monopoly covers all forms of liquid milk for direct human
consumption including skimmed and semi-skimmed milk. The Commission
disagrees, claiming that the MMBs' exclusive rights are limited to whole
milk.
The ECJ president, who customarily decides interim measures cases alone, did
not examine the merits of the dispute, rejecting the Commission's
application on the ground of lack of urgency.
In particular, he held that the milk producers concerned had sufficient
safeguards that the status quo would be maintained until judgment by the
full court without danger of serious and irreparable damage. He accepted
undertakings by the MMBs not to enforce any rights over skimmed or
semi-skimmed milk until the ECJ's final decision.
Commission v UK, Case C-40/92 R, Order of the President of the Court, 22 May
1992.
Permissible national controls - auditors
The ECJ has delivered another significant judgment for the professions, and
in particular auditors, building on earlier indications of the kind of
national controls which member states may impose on individuals or companies
established in one member state when they provide services or are engaged as
employees in a second member state.
In accordance with EC rules on establishment, an auditor authorised to
practise in Luxembourg under Luxembourg law, and employed by an authorised
Luxembourg company, may not have his authorisation removed simply on the
ground that he no longer satisfies the condition of Luxembourg law which
restricts authorisation to auditors established in Luxembourg, when he moves
his centre of operations to Germany, and is employed by a German company
related to his Luxembourg employer.
However, the Rome Treaty rules on free movement of workers and freedom to
provide services permit Luxembourg to require the auditor to comply with
certain rules which can be objectively justified in the public interest and
are equally applicable to Luxembourg auditors, if the requirements in the
member state where he is established are not equivalent.
In the current case, this meant that, within its own territory, Luxembourg
could require compliance with rules objectively necessary to ensure
professional rules applicable to auditors are observed, and require an
effective presence and a permanent infrastructure in Luxembourg as well as
the supervision of an auditor's compliance with professional ethics.
Ramrath v Minister of Justice, Case C-106/91, 6CH 20 May 1992.
Cheaper German roads
The ECJ had condemned a German law, previously suspended in 1990 by interim
order of the Court, increasing the tax imposed on heavy lorries using
Federal roads.
The tax was held to infringe the Rome Treaty's 'standstill' rule prohibiting
the introduction of new road transport measures with the direct or indirect
effect of discriminating against transport from other member states.
The discrimination resulted from the fact that, while German road hauliers
were subject to the same increase, they received a reduction in motor
vehicle tax which was not shared by those from other member states.
This judgment will save road hauliers of all member states the additional
costs when crossing Germany, in particular, to eastern Europe.
Commission v Germany, Case C-195/90, FC 19 May 1992.
Other cases
In four cases of less general significance, the ECJ rejected cases brought
by Greece challenging the clearance of its 1987 CAP accounts (Case C-385/89)
and by the Commission against Germany unsuccessfully claiming that German
rules infringed the Treaty rules on free movement of goods by applying
stricter rules to eye drops as a result of defining them as medicinal
products instead of as cosmetics (Case C-290/90).
The court upheld the Commission in finding that the Netherlands had failed
to implement correctly, within the time laid down, the 1982 directive on
risks of certain big industrial accidents (Case C-190/90) as well as
interpreting certain terms in the directive on the treatment of employees in
the case of the transfer of undertakings in the special context of certain
Dutch social work foundations (Case C-29/91).
FT Commercial Law Reports
Following the introduction of the European Court column, FT commercial law
reports now appear on Wednesdays, Thursdays and Fridays. There will be no
European Court column next week as the court is not sitting.
All dairy farmers in the same situation as those in last week's test cases
will be entitled to claim damages caused by invalid EC rules on the
additional milk levy quota introduced in 1984
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
