<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Security-aware design urged for buildings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POLICE yesterday launched a campaign to incorporate crime prevention into
the design of commercial buildings.
Secured by Design, an initiative that orginally applied only to new
residential properties, has been extended to new and renovated commercial
properties.
Last year there were 550,000 commercial and 600,000 domestic burglaries, but
police say that simple measures, such as good lighting for footpaths and car
parks, can deter burglars.
Developers are to be encouraged to consult police crime prevention experts
at an early stage and to incorporate security features in building
specifications. Properties that meet police guidelines can then be marketed
using the Secured by Design logo as a selling point.
Advice from police architectural liaison officers will be free, and the
publicity campaign is being sponsored by lock-makers and other providers of
security equipment.
Crime-prevention officers recommended that even the layout of an estate,
whether commercial or residential, should be planned with security in mind.
Barriers should create well defined 'defensible space' around estates and
individual properties.
</TEXT>
