FT  27 MAY 92 / Greenpeace criticises Earth Summit agenda
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINA LAMB
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GREENPEACE, the environ-mental activist organisation, has accused organisers
of next week's Earth Summit of allowing it to be 'hijacked by industry' and
failing to include in the conference agenda any controls on industrial
activities.
At a press conference in Rio de Janeiro, Mr Kenny Bruno, co-ordinator of the
Greenpeace Hazardous Export/Import Project, said the Summit had 'adopted
industry's line that first world corporations have the capacity to spread
environmentally sound, sustainable technologies thoughout the world'. The
truth was that they remained 'the primary creators of dirty, dangerous and
unsustainable technologies and are at the root of all the world's main
environmental problems.'
Mr Bruno accused companies of 'greenwash', which he said meant 'hiding
environmentally destructive practices behind environmental images and
language stolen from the ecological movement'.
In a report Greenpeace examines the records of big companies which Mr Bruno
claims 'are proclaiming environmentalism' while continuing to cause damage.
