<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Dual approach to electricity sell-offs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK GRAY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SINGAPORE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SOUTH-EAST Asian nations are moving towards a dual approach to privatisation
and restructuring of their electricity supply industries, the Financial
Times Asian Electricity Conference was told yesterday.
The pattern evolving among key members of the Association of South-east
Asian Nations (Asean) - Malaysia, Indonesia, Thailand and the Philippines -
was for independent, private power generators in competition for electricity
sales with the state utilities, and for the longer-term restructuring of the
state companies aimed at selling their shares on the region's stock
exchanges.
The pace is being set by Malaysia's state utility Tenaga Nasional Berhad, 23
per cent of whose shares were recently sold by subscription to institutions
and individual investors in the country's biggest state-sector share
flotation. Trading in the shares on the Kuala Lumpur stock exchange is
imminent.
Mr S. Samy Vellu, the Malaysian energy minister, said the flotation had been
substantially oversubscribed and more shares could go on the market soon if
a strong price was established.
Other Asean nations have their own privatisation programmes, but their
approach tends to be to invite independent power generators to set up
alongside national utilities. Restructuring of the state companies would
come later, and a cautious approach would be taken to any sell-off of state
assets, the conference was told.
Mr Artono Arismunandar, Indonesia's director-general of electricity, said
his country already had a lot of private-sector power operating alongside
the PLN, the state utility, but most was for own-use in industrial estates
and company towns. The country aimed to boost sale of surplus private power
to the national grid and to invite new private power generators to share in
new projects.
Mr Danilo Cantiller, economics department manager for the National Power
Corporation of the Philippines (NPC), said his country had an open-door
policy to private-sector power generating companies to supplement the output
of the NPC. Enabling legislation declaring that the PLN was no longer a
natural monopoly was passed in 1987.
A study of the possible break-up and privatisation of the NPC was being
undertaken.
Mr Piyasvasti Amranand of Thailand's National Energy Policy Office said the
abolition of trade unions at the Electricity Generating Authority of
Thailand several years ago had made it possible for the authority to
consider some form of privatisation.
</TEXT>
