</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BANGKOK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THAILAND'S acting government yesterday lifted a state of emergency imposed
on Bangkok and four surrounding provinces during violent confrontations
between pro-democracy demonstrators and troops last week.
The authorities banned public gatherings under the state of emergency, but
protesters ignored the order. At least 48 people were killed by the armed
forces before the king of Thailand brokered a compromise and Gen Suchinda
Kraprayoon, the prime minister, was forced to resign.
The five-party coalition government which appointed Gen Suchinda bowed to
popular pressure on Monday and approved constitutional amendments demanded
by the opposition to reduce the power of the military.
Yesterday the pro-military coalition appeared to be on the brink of falling
apart as its members attempted to choose a new prime minister and faced
demands for the punishment of the senior military officers responsible for
the shootings.
Various solutions are being aired, including a new coalition which would
bring in some of the opposition parties, and the possibility of new
elections.
There is widespread concern the military will feel cornered by demands for
retribution and stage a coup d'etat. Opposition parties have asked the
constitutional tribunal to rescind an amnesty decree signed by Gen Suchinda
which pardons demonstrators and those who gave the troops the order to
shoot.
