<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Fall of the tireless salaryman: Signs of a decline in
Japan's famed work ethic
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HAVING bickered with his daughter over the choice of daytime television
dramas, the holiday-stricken salaryman grabs his golf clubs and heads for
the driving range. In the cartoon's next frame, he slices the ball, smashing
a window in an adjacent house. In the end, not knowing where to turn, he
seeks refuge back at the office, behind his faithful desk.
Once the hero, portrayed in the glorious style of socialist realism, the
factory and office 'warrior' dedicated to building a strong Japan has become
a media-mocked buffoon, lacking in social skills, alienated from his family,
and comfortable only in the company of his desk. Young Japanese laugh at the
thought of emulating him, and company managers are aghast at the pointed
criticism that has skewered the salaryman.
The salaryman's fall from grace is part of a larger debate over the fate of
the country's famed work ethic, said to be under siege by modern comforts
and a creeping, corrupting individualism. This theory is partly inspired by
the recurring nightmare that Japan has 'peaked', that the economy is in
quickening decline and that directionless Japanese youth will lead the
country into mediocrity.
Mr Akio Morita, Sony chairman, regarded as Japan's Prince Charles for his
sometimes lofty though not irrelevant observations, relaunched the debate a
few weeks ago with an unexpected confession that employees are underpaid and
overworked. He said companies have failed to recognise that the era of
aggressive growth has passed and, essentially, should be more caring and
sharing.
The timing of Mr Morita's comments, just before the annual wage bargaining
season, drew gasps of disbelief from other executives who saw the Sony boss
as loading the heavy artillery for the unions. However, Japanese unions are
weaker than at any time in recent history and quickly agreed to small pay
rises after a half-day ceremonial strike by train drivers, who later offered
humble apologies for the inconvenience caused.
With wage negotiations out of the way, Japanese executives have felt free to
express their opinions on the work ethic, and not all disagree with Mr
Morita. Meanwhile, Mr Kiichi Miyazawa, the prime minister, has just received
two reports from special committees drafting a New Economic Plan to better
balance the priorities of GNP growth and lifestyle.
One report urged that Japan become a 'lifestyle superpower', as opposed to a
military or economic superpower. And, as one way of attaining this distant
goal, recommended that the country's commuter trains, famed for those
white-gloved guards who shove excess passengers into already crammed
carriages, be 10 per cent less crowded.
Another committee found, as committees have in the past, that the present
economic structure focuses too much on the company and too little on the
consumer, and that while statistically wealthy, Japanese do not feel
affluent. But this government committee went further, encouraging the
individualism that is widely seen as a threat to 'groupism', company
loyalty, and the work ethic.
'We must make Japan a society in which people can attain a better quality of
life, an equitable society where every citizen can both appreciate a
comfortable and leisurely lifestyle, and have equal opportunities to develop
an individual sense of values,' the report recommended.
A survey of 2,125 corporate executives by the Keidanren, the employers
federation, showed support for shorter working hours and recognition that
the salaryman did not have a leisurely lifestyle. This executive support was
tempered by the beliefs that Japan 'cannot afford' to reduce the working
week and that Japanese had an innate love of work.
But a majority of executives also said this 'love' was fading among younger
workers, the shinjinrui or new breed, who see no role model in the
middle-aged, desk-bound salaryman. By repute, the ethic-less younger
generation will take holidays, swap jobs, and refuse to compromise personal
interests for the company good.
The changes are more in attitude than action. A separate survey of 10,000
residents by the prime minister's office found, across all age groups and
both sexes, that only 24 per cent thought personal fulfilment more important
than the national interest, though among males aged between 25 and 29, the
figure was 39 per cent.
Yet graduates' choice of companies this year showed a clear bias towards the
neatly drawn career path and lifetime employment offered by the typical
large company and the bureaucracy. Meanwhile, the onset of recession has
encouraged the electronics makers, which pioneered the unorthodox practice
of mid-career hiring, to reduce this intake to a few specialist staff.
'I thought about working in a small company or starting my own business, but
it was safer to work for a big financial company,' said a graduate who
joined Yamaichi Securities a year ago. He did not particularly like the work
or the weight of the hierarchy bearing down on him, but 'I don't really have
a choice'.
Rather than young Japanese breaking the social contract, some troubled
industries are now tempted to lay off staff. Securities companies increased
their employees by 41.6 per cent over the four years to 1990, and the
mid-sized brokers, most bruised by the stock market collapse, are trying to
find a way to close branches without making staff redundant.
The government, meanwhile, will soon have to reschedule the official
timetable for the reduction of working hours. The aim was to get the
official average working year down from 2,050 hours to 1,800 hours by next
year. Unpaid overtime pushes the total as high as 3,000 hours in industries
such as banking. But, in the Keidanren survey, 44 per cent of companies were
not sure that the 1,800 target could be reached by the end of the century.
'One's life is made up of time, and this should be better understood,'
explained a sympathetic executive at Coal Resources Development, a coal
importer. But the case of another resources company is more illuminating -
Mitsubishi Oil became suddenly famous two years ago when news surfaced of a
scheme to fine employees who did not take their full complement of holidays.
The truth is that the scheme involved only seven employees in one small
section of the crude oil import division. Last year, four of the seven
workers failed to take a total of 14 days' holiday and the Y14,000 in fines
went to buy beer and sake for their end-of-year party.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 4
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-6198</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CE0AWAAVFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920527
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Chiefs, Indians and Rabuka go to polls in Fiji: Bullets or
ballots, this time Fiji's military ruler wants to take power in an election
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MAJOR General Sitiveni Rabuka has taken power in Fiji twice since 1987, each
time at the point of a gun. This week, he hopes to take power again, through
the more unpredictable mechanism of the ballot box.
Almost exactly five years after Mr Rabuka's first armed intervention,
Fijians are voting in a general election organised by an interim civilian
government.
The election will almost certainly return the ethnic Fijian Soqosoqo ni
Vakavulewa ni Taukei (SVT) party, led by Mr Rabuka, as the largest
parliamentary group. But it seems unlikely to resolve the underlying
tensions among Fiji's 345,000 ethnic Fijians, 340,000 Indians and 35,000
Europeans, Chinese, Polynesians and other races.
The army took power in May 1987 in the name of ethnic Fijian nationalism,
claiming that a coalition government dominated by Indians was making Fijians
second-class citizens in their own country. It was a message which made Mr
Rabuka a hero to many ethnic Fijians, especially when the army intervened a
second time to torpedo a compromise agreement which would have given the
coalition a continued role in government.
But by focusing on a single cause of tension, the nationalist rhetoric
obscured the underlying reasons for the coup, which had at least as much to
do with regional and class conflicts as with race.
The election of the coalition gave Indians a leading role in Fijian
government for the first time since their forebears arrived to work on sugar
plantations during British colonial rule. But the coalition also contained a
number of ethnic Fijians representing the trade-union based Fiji Labour
party, which wanted to reduce the influence of the chiefs, the traditional
leaders of ethnic Fijian society.
Furthermore, many of the Labour MPs came from the west of Viti Levu, Fiji's
main island, which has long resented the influence of the eastern-based
chiefly establishment. The constitution drawn up by the interim government
seeks to entrench ethnic Fijian political domination by reserving 37 of the
70 seats in the lower house of parliament. Indians have been allocated 27
seats, and other races five; one is reserved for the Polynesian island of
Rotuma.
In addition, the prime minister must be an ethnic Fijian, and veto power on
many issues has been given to a senate composed entirely of ethnic Fijians
selected by the Great Council of Chiefs, a traditional advisory body. The
constitution also seeks to entrench village values by over-representing
rural ethnic Fijians at the expense of urban voters who are more likely to
oppose chiefly influence.
In effect, the system is a compromise between Mr Rabuka and Fiji's elder
statesmen, Ratu Sir Penaia Ganilau, the former governor-general who is now
president, and Ratu Sir Kamisese Mara, the interim prime minister. Both
chiefs are believed to have argued for a less confrontational approach to
the Indian community, while supporting the objective of buttressing chiefly
influence.
However, the voting system means the SVT can only govern alone if it wins
almost all the ethnic Fijian seats. That is unlikely to happen, mainly
because of growing support for the more extreme Fijian Nationalist United
Front (FNUF), which has called for the expulsion of Indians. The SVT could
also lose some seats to the multiracial All National Congress, which would
probably line up with Indian opponents of the constitution.
The arithmetic is complicated by the Labour party's promise that its MPs
will boycott parliament, which would lower the threshold for a working
majority. But the most likely outcome is a hung parliament in which the FNUF
holds the balance of power.
If that happens, Ratu Sir Penaia will almost certainly have to appoint Mr
Rabuka head of an SVT/FNUF coalition government, which would be a
frightening prospect for many Indians. Indian business leaders say such an
outcome could lead to a further wave of emigration as better-off Indians
follow the example of the 23,000 largely professional workers who left after
the coups of 1987.
However, most Indians appear willing to stay provided there is no repetition
of the inter-racial violence which followed the first coup in 1987. Many
have extensive business interests which they would be reluctant to abandon.
In the longer term, both ethnic Fijians and Indians say the country has a
bright future if it can achieve stable government and maintain the strong
growth in tourism and manufacturing it has enjoyed under the interim
government.
On present trends, that is likely to happen in the early years of the next
century. Meanwhile, voters must wait until Sunday to learn the result of the
week-long election, which is taking place on more than 300 islands scattered
over more than 700,000 square kilometres of the South Pacific. This time, Mr
Rabuka must wait too.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 4
</PAGE>
