<PROFILE>_AN-CE0AWAATFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920527
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / World Trade News: US set to spill beans on its EC oilseeds
'retaliation' - Dollars 1bn in sanctions being considered in Washington to
offset 'unfair' European subsidies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BUSH administration is debating a list of Dollars 1bn in sanctions it is
threatening to impose on European Community products in retaliation for the
EC's oilseeds regime which the US claims has cost it billions in soyabean
sales.
Foods, wines and beer are likely to head the list, but a number of US
officials believe it might provoke a greater outcry if industrial products
are included. The question has been forwarded to the Bush cabinet for
discussion, perhaps as early as this week, after an interagency group
committee was unable to agree.
For its part, the EC has yet to decide how to respond to the US threats. It
is said to be considering a compensation proposal. Complicating the issue is
the agreement reached last week by the EC farm ministers to reform the
Common Agricultural Policy, and the possibility that the changes ultimately
will at least partly address US complaints by reducing EC oilseeds
production.
The US made public its intention on April 30 to impose sanctions after the
EC blocked a report finding that EC oilseeds subsidies were illegal under
the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. The EC indicated that it would
accept the report at a Gatt Council meeting in June and at the same time
propose a remedy.
Meanwhile, the Bush Administration, unasked, is getting industry's ideas.
The National Association of Wheat Growers, for example, has recommended new
tariffs on pasta and wheat gluten to level the 'uneven playing field'. US
imports of EC pasta, made from heavily subsidised wheat, have increased 70
per cent in the past decade.
Both the Uruguay Round and the oilseeds dispute are expected to be on the
agenda when Mr Frans Andriessen, the EC commissioner in charge of trade, and
other EC officials meet today with Mr James Baker, the US secretary of
state; Mrs Carla Hills, the US trade representative, and Mr Edward Madigan,
the US agriculture secretary.
Without a breakthrough Mrs Hills is likely to roll out a list containing
Dollars 2bn in sanctions for 30 days of public comment, after which the list
will be pared.
Mrs Hills talks of how she was promised 'with a handshake' that the
subsidies would be 'fixed' in time for the 1991 growing season. US patience
has been 'rather endless,' she said, but if the Gatt process is to have any
credibility, she must act.
The role of domestic politics cannot be dismissed. Mrs Hills says President
Bush has clung fast to his free-trade principles, though only 35-40 per cent
of US farmers support his position in the Uruguay Round.
There are no senators who do not have farmers in their districts, she said.
'There are some districts that are 100 per cent agricultural and could
indeed tip the election.'
The EC oilseeds programme, which set Community prices at about double the
prevailing world levels, was designed to draw Community farmers away from
surplus grain production. Between 1980-1990, EC producers more than tripled
the land area devoted to EC production of rapeseed, sunflower seed and
soyabeans, and boosted planting from 4m to 13m acres. At the same time US
exports of soyabeans fell 63 per cent.
In 1987 the American Soyabean Association gave up waiting for farm reform in
the Uruguay Round to solve the problem and filed a case against the EC
oilseeds regime, which the US trade representative took to the Gatt. After
many delays, a Gatt panel concluded in 1990 that the subsidies impaired the
advantage the EC had promised when in 1962 it agreed to 'bind' its oilseed
import tariffs at zero duty.
After more postponements, the EC revised its oilseeds regime. Instead of
making payments to oilseeds processors for using EC oilseeds, it would make
them directly to EC farmers. In the US view, this was an improvement because
the regime no longer discriminated against foreign oilseeds, but it still
subsidised production and thus devalued the advantage promised when zero
tariffs were negotiated.
The US returned to the Gatt, where a panel again found against the EC
oilseeds regime. The EC blocked adoption of the panel's report on April 30
but promised a 'concrete proposal' for settlement before the June 1992 Gatt
Council meeting. The US indicated that it would impose sanctions if the
proposal was not satisfactory.
EC officials, who complain that the US is impatient and impulsive, say the
Bush administration is acting 'totally without justification' and lacks
legal basis because the oilseeds report is still pending. American officials
see the EC as consistently delaying the inevitable; they believe that by
blocking the panel report the EC is violating the spirit of the Gatt and
they have the right to take action.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 3
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-6201</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CE0AWAASFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920527
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Caretaker government imposes further three-month freeze on
capital spending in Italy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ITALY'S caretaker government yesterday imposed a further three-month freeze
on capital spending projects in a symbolic gesture to answer the EC's recent
harsh criticism of the country's public finances, writes Robert Graham.
In January, the government imposed for a six-month period a series of stiff
requirements for approval of capital spending projects to hold down the
public sector deficit, which was rising beyond 10.5 per cent of GDP. The
main effect of this measure was to permit the Treasury to scrutinise all
large investment requests and withhold approval unless ample justification
was provided. Yesterday's cabinet meeting extended this procedure until
September.
The saving will be little more than L1,000bn (Pounds 452.7m), against this
year's projected deficit of more than L165,000bn.  But the authorities were
anxious to signal to Brussels that public spending would be closely
monitored while a new government is being formed.
</TEXT>
