<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Italian 'Mr Clean' emerges from a dirty fight: Mr Oscar
Luigi Scalfaro, the new president, is the product of compromise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Oscar Luigi Scalfaro, who will be sworn in as Italy's ninth president on
Thursday, has a personality and style in sharp contrast to his predecessor,
Mr Francesco Cossiga.
Courteous, devoutly Catholic, and formal, the new president, 73, could not
be more different from the loquacious and unpredictable Mr Cossiga. Although
both have come to the presidency from the ruling Christian Democrat party,
Mr Scalfaro has always kept his distance from the inner cabals - unlike Mr
Cossiga.
Mr Cossiga rejoiced in his self-appointed populist role as 'the man with a
pick-axe', chipping away at a political system in urgent need of reform. Mr
Scalfaro projects the image of an impartial father figure, steering the ship
of state along the path of reform with the limited powers available to the
head of state. Mr Scalfaro was taken on as a 'Mr Clean'. Indeed, eyebrows
have been raised by his ultra-conservatism. When chosen as speaker of the
chamber of deputies after the April 5 general election, he had his office
sprinkled with holy water and in the past is credited with telling a woman
in a restaurant her decollete was too revealing.
Perhaps not surprisingly he and Mr Cossiga can scarcely speak to each other.
Mr Cossiga was deeply affronted when Mr Scalfaro became the new speaker
against his express wishes - a key element in the latter's resignation on
April 25, two months before his seven-year term was complete.
In his brief period as speaker, Mr Scalfaro impressed with his scrupulous
impartiality. When voting for the presidency began on May 13 he was
considered a potential compromise candidate, but it required 16 voting
sessions of the joint houses of parliament to endorse him in the final round
(there were 1,010 potential voters).
Although this may have seemed an unnecessarily long period to elect a new
head of state when the country was without a government, the election
process was treated by the parties as a dress rehearsal for the formation of
the next government. Thus the first three sessions tested whether the
outgoing four-party coalition of Christian Democrats, Socialists, Liberals
and Social Democrats could rely on their members to fall behind the
leadership choice.
This failed, as the Christian Democrats in particular were deeply divided.
The Christian Democrats then played their main card, proposing Mr Arnaldo
Forlani, the party secretary general, in the fifth and sixth vote. He
mustered no more than 479 votes, short of the 508 majority, and should have
won 60 votes more if all the coalition had backed him.
The failure of Mr Forlani was crucial. He received insufficient support
because he was too openly identified with a discredited system of Christian
Democrat-controlled power, out of touch with the reforming mood of the
country. The rebuff applied equally to another Christian Democrat
heavyweight, Mr Giulio Andreotti, the outgoing prime minister. Unable to
unite his party, Mr Forlani resigned last Friday.
The Forlani resignation symbolised the impotence of the ruling coalition and
allowed the search for a Christian Democrat compromise 'institutional'
candidate in the form of Mr Scalfaro.
Mr Scalfaro received 672 of the 1,002 votes present. This included the vote
of the former communist Party of the Democratic Left (PDS), the radicals and
the Greens, but not the republicans, who were upset that their strong
front-runner, Mr Giovanni Spadolini, the interim president, was passed over.
This voting alliance demonstrates that the politicians have taken on board
the public demand for electoral and institutional reform evident in the big
general election protest vote.
The politicians were also conditioned in their choice by the need to present
a 'clean' candidate in the light of growing public unease over the Milan
corruption scandal.
</TEXT>
