<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 92 / Soviet communist party to go on trial: Old regime likened to
Nazis as Moscow prepares to judge Lenin and his heirs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE communist party of the Soviet Union (CPSU) was yesterday sent for trial
for violations of the constitution of the Soviet Union, the state which it
created.
The trial, timed for July 7, will be a public judgment on the darkest
chapters of the history of the USSR since the 1917 revolution. Mr Andrei
Makarov, the legal counsel of Mr Boris Yeltsin, the Russian President, set
the tone when he likened the CPSU to the German Nazi Party - many of whose
leaders were put on trial at Nuremberg after the last war. Mr Gennady
Burbulis, Mr Yeltsin's top aide, said after the decision of the
Constitutional Court that further action might be taken against specific
leaders of the CPSU.
The decision of the court to, in effect, put the Party's history on trial
came ironically as a result of a suit brought to the court by communist
deputies, alleging that President Yeltsin's decrees banning the CPSU and the
Russian Communist Party after the August coup were unconstitutional.
This was countered by a cross suit brought by Mr Oleg Rumyantsev, leader of
the Social Democratic Party, that the CPSU had violated the Soviet
constitution.
The collegium of judges on the bench decided to unite both suits in one  -
to the vociferous protests of the many once senior communists in the court -
including Mr Yegor Ligachev, formerly number two in the politburo to Mr
Mikhail Gorbachev, and Mr Vladimir Ivashko, Mr Gorbachev's deputy at the
time of the coup.
The judgment, described by Mr Burbulis as 'brilliant', means that even if Mr
Yeltsin's decrees are ultimately judged unconstitutional, the country will
be convulsed by promised revelations on the party's murderous past. Mr
Gorbachev, the party's last general secretary and, in his role as president,
the man who presided over its dissolution, was not himself in court. Mr
Burbulis hinted that the court's decision would damage the former
president's efforts to rehabilitate himself when he said: 'I doubt he will
now engage in further political activity.'
Mr Valery Zorkin, the court's chairman, ruled that former party leaders,
including Mr Gorbachev, could represent the party if they wished. Mr
Yeltsin's side had argued that the party had no legal standing in the court
because of the ban on its activities. Mr Sergei Shakhrai, legal aide to Mr
Yeltsin, has already given a hint of the evidence to be brought against the
party when he produced a document on Monday which showed that the CPSU had
authorised shipments of weapons in 1975 to the Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine, the most militantly terrorist of the groups within
the Palestinian Liberation Organisation.
Mr Yeltsin said yesterday he would not resign from office during his current
term but did not plan to stand for a second spell in 1996, according to
Itar-Tass news agency.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
