<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 92 / UK Company News: Montedison tumbles 70% to L168bn but
maintains payout
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP-DJ and HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MONTEDISON, the Italian chemical and agribusiness concern controlled by the
Ferruzzi family, reported consolidated net profits of L168bn in 1991, a drop
of 70 per cent drop on the previous year's L556bn, but proposed leaving its
annual dividend unchanged at L50, AP-DJ reports from Milan.
The group blamed the sharp drop in profits on the fact that 1990 earnings
had been boosted by the sale of its stake in Enimont, the former joint
venture with state energy group Ente Nazionale Idrocarburi.
Montedison said gross operating earnings rose 12 per cent to L1,828bn last
year from L1,631 in 1990.
The improvement in the group's operating results was entirely due to its
agroindustrial unit Eridania, which reported a gross operating margin of
L1,025bn, up 15 per cent from L891bn in 1990.
Operating results at Montecatini, the chemical division, slipped 2 per cent
to L875bn from L891bn. Better results at its pharmaceuticals, specialty
chemicals, specialty polymers and energy divisions were eroded by the
tighter margins in the polymers market, which suffered from sluggish demand
in the car, construction and electronics industry, Montedison said.
IFIL. the Italian holding company which specialises in the food and hotels
sectors and is controlled by the Agnelli family, raised net group profits by
42 per cent to L162.5bn last year, Haig Simonian reports from Milan.
Net earnings at parent company level climbed 10.8 per cent to L105.5bn,
prompting a L10 a share increase in the dividend to L130 for ordinary shares
and L150 for savings stock.
In an expansion of its hotel activities, IFIL said it now owned 2 per cent
of Accor, the French hotels chain, with which it already operates two joint
ventures in Italy. The holding had been bought for around L70bn through the
Paris bourse and with Accor management's approval.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
