<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 92 / Universities seek big state funds rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNIVERSITY CHIEFS have told the government that direct state funding for
universities needs to rise by more than a fifth - Pounds 400m - next year if
the quality of teaching and research is to be maintained as student numbers
rise.
In a submission to Mr John Patten, education secretary, for the 1993-94
public expenditure round, the committee of vice-chancellors and principals
points to the 9 per cent increase in university student numbers this year
and projections of a similar increase next year. The committee is seeking an
extra Pounds 450m in funding and believes universities can raise only Pounds
56m of it themselves.
The largest item - Pounds 165m - is to fund a salary increase in real terms
for existing academic staff 'to provide incentives for the radical and rapid
changes in teaching methods and course design now needed'.
The submission also includes Pounds 39m for new staff, Pounds 73m to improve
the pay of non-academic staff and Pounds 150m - almost double the existing
capital allocation to the Universities Funding Council - for 'essential'
improvements to plant and facilities.
The committee says: 'The key issue for universities in the 1990s is how to
achieve further expansion in line with their own and government's plans
without jeopardising the quality of their teaching and research.'
It expresses particular concern about academic pay levels, which have fallen
far behind the non-manual average in the past decade. The vice-chancellors
urge the establishment of a pay review body for higher education similar to
that accorded to school teachers, whose salary increases have far
outstripped those for academics in the past two years.
'As the government brings other comparable groups into the scope of pay
review bodies, it becomes progressively more difficult to explain to
university staff why they should be excluded,' the vice-chancellors say.
However, universities are unlikely to fare well in a tight public spending
round because schools are the government's priority for education spending.
</TEXT>
