FT  26 MAY 92 / MPs press Bank chief over Maxwell pensions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE all-party group of MPs campaigning on behalf of the Maxwell pensioners
is likely to seek a meeting with Mr Robin Leigh-Pemberton, governor of the
Bank of England, when it meets next week.
The prospect of further pressure on the Bank comes as the government faces
renewed calls to compensate thousands of elderly pensioners who belong to
collapsed pension schemes of the late Mr Robert Maxwell's companies.
The 100-plus MPs are unhappy about the Bank's apparently relaxed view of its
supervisory role and believe that recent comments by Mr Leigh-Pemberton have
been unhelpful. These complaints were raised last week by Mr Richard Page
and Mr Frank Field, representing the group, with Mr Peter Lilley, social
security secretary, who 'willingly' undertook to pass them on to the Bank.
The group has no powers to compel attendance, as cross-party select
committees do, but the large number of MPs, including at least one minister,
who are taking an active interest in the issue mean that Mr Leigh-Pemberton
would come under considerable pressure to explain the Bank's approach to the
group.
Ministers are said to be pressing the pension-fund industry to devise a
scheme which could compensate the Maxwell pensioners.
Some of the MPs campaigning on behalf of the pensioners also believe that an
industry scheme offers the best way forward.
The government is unwilling to bear the cost of replacing the Pounds 400m
said to be missing from the Maxwell schemes, fearing that it could set a
precedent. Ministers have repeatedly ruled out the idea of a government
compensation scheme.
However, campaigners have been encouraged by what they believe is a more
positive approach from the government, which may be more sympathetic because
of a report from the Securities and Investments Board to be published soon.
The report may point to failings by Imro, the regulatory body for the
fund-management industry, in supervising and authorising Bishopsgate
Investment Management, which managed assets of all the Maxwell companies'
pension schemes. The pensioners believe that they are entitled to government
compensation because, they say, government departments mishandled the
supervision of Bishopsgate.
The National Association of Pension Funds is considering an industry-funded
scheme but opinion is divided. Mr Brian McMahon, association chairman, said
that letters to him show little support for a compensation scheme.
</TEXT>
