<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 92 / UK Council Services: Setting up shop in the council
marketplace
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPULSORY competitive tendering is still in its infancy. Although a few
adventurous Tory councils contracted out services in the mid 1980s,
compulsory tendering officially began less than four years ago. Before then,
most councillors of all parties - not just Labour - resisted the idea, and
addressed it seriously only after the 1988 Local Government Act forced them
to.
The learning curve has been steeper still for companies, faced not only by
the formidable legal complexities of bidding, but by the variety of type of
work and size of contracts. Councils range from tiny rural districts to
large metropolitan authorities.
The act specifies services to be put out to tender and the authorities
obliged to tender them - all district and county councils, as well as
police, fire and waste authorities and urban development corporations. It
also sets out a framework, the most notable features of which are the length
of contracts - mostly between five and seven years; a detailed procedure for
inviting tenders - at least three companies expressing an interest must be
invited to tender; an exemption from tendering for services with an annual
contract value of less than Pounds 100,000; a requirement on local-authority
in-house teams to make a 5 per cent annual rate of return on capital
employed, and provisions to prevent anti-competitive behaviour.
Such behaviour has been exceptional, even among Labour authorities. In most
councils the tendering process is in the hands of officers, with members
involved only in setting specifications and formally allocating contracts.
The Department of the Environment has issued only 44 orders requiring
authorities to explain their action over a contract. More frequent are
complaints from companies about the packaging of contracts in a way to suit
the in-house team.
As the first round of tendering draws to a close, the study highlights
significant trends:
Refuse collection and street cleaning: with more than a quarter of contracts
now held by the private sector, this has proved the most fruitful area.
Councils traditionally used a single department to run both services, and a
large proportion of contracts are for both services. The average value of
contracts is accordingly high, at around Pounds 1.2m.
The early stages of tendering saw a number of management buy-outs, notably
at Westminster City Council where MRS Environmental Services won a Pounds
12m contract and has gone on to secure three others totalling Pounds 4m.
Since then subsidiaries of French and Spanish multinationals have moved to
the fore. Onyx UK, the largest player with 20 contracts worth Pounds 25m a
year, was formed by two French water companies in 1990 and its subsequent
growth has largely been through acquisitions of British concerns - notably
UK Waste - which specialise in local-authority work.
The private sector has fared increasingly well in the past two years. Its
share of contracts has risen from 14 per cent of the August 1990 tranche to
half of those awarded this January. Its success has not been limited to
smaller packages: private contractors have done better in London than any
other region, taking 43 per cent of the capital's market.
Building cleaning: by proportion of contracts, this is the most successful
field for the private sector, which won a majority of contracts awarded at
the start of this year. Since the work is labour-intensive, with low
start-up costs, its success is perhaps unsurprising. Local authorities have
tended to split the work in two, contracting school cleaning separately.
Civic cleaning, the smaller of the two operations, has proved most
attractive to private operators. Initial Contract Services, owned by BET,
the UK's largest contract services company, is the lead player, with 47
contracts worth Pounds 17m a year.
Catering: in spite of the private sector's experience in catering, it has
made little impact, winning fewer than a tenth of contracts. School and
welfare catering has proved particularly unattractive to private operators,
given the number of outlets, and term and pricing constraints. Smaller
contracts in other areas have proved more enticing, but catering remains the
untrodden field of tendering. Grounds maintenance: councils were obliged to
tender for this sector over a five-year period, and a large tranche of
first-round contracts has still to be awarded this year and next. Contract
specifications have proved difficult. The main private player - Brophy, with
53 contracts worth Pounds 14m a year - was tiny prior to tendering.
Grounds maintenance has attracted a large number of successful cross-border
bids by council teams, with one in 10 contracts awarded to another council's
direct-labour service. The legality of the practice is hotly disputed but
has yet to be tested directly in the courts.
Leisure services: everything from swimming pools to golf courses, with
facilities and practices varying enormously between authorities. The sector
is proving susceptible to management buy-outs. But councils retain control
over admissions prices and opening hours.
There are two useful tips for potential bidders say those in the know. Meet
council officers at an early stage - particularly to ascertain the quality
of service expected, which is often ill-defined in the specification. And do
not underestimate the cost of bidding - most of all the first time round.
Vehicle maintenance: private companies have taken almost a fifth of the
market. Local-authority practice in transferring vehicle stock with
responsibility for maintenance varies widely, as do arrangements for depot
facilities. Half of all contracts fall between Pounds 100,000 and Pounds
500,000, and more authorities have declared their contracts de minimis in
this sector than in any other.
More than half of all tendered contracts have gone to four leading
companies. Transfleet Services, a joint venture between Lex Services and
Lombard North Central, which merged with Chart Services UK in 1989, has been
most successful, holding nine contracts worth Pounds 4.7m a year.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-6259</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEZASADHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920526
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 92 / UK Council Services: Town halls fall to the commercial
revolution - Contracts awarded to date total Pounds 1.9bn a year / From
refuse collection to leisure management the provision of services is big
business
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NICHOLAS RIDLEY'S vision of local authorities meeting once a year to hand
out contracts may not be shared by the post-Thatcher regime. But the phrase
'enabling councils' is on all politicians' lips - and compulsory competitive
tendering (CCT) is seen by the government as one way of creating them.
The survey below summarises a comprehensive study of the effect of tendering
on local authorities across Great Britain, published today by the Institute
of Public Finance, a research arm of the Chartered Institute of Public
Finance and Accountancy. It will be followed by regular FT updates, based on
CCT bulletins to be published by the institute, on the position sector by
sector.
Tendering is worth big money. Contracts awarded to date total Pounds 1.9bn a
year, with the typical refuse collection contract alone worth Pounds 1.2m a
year.
The private sector is advancing steadily. Its share of the local authority
market is now appreciable: of the seven main sectors currently subject to
tendering - refuse collection, street cleaning, building cleaning, vehicle
maintenance, grounds maintenance, sports and leisure management and catering
 -in all but one (catering) private operators have won more than 18 per cent
of contracts put out to tender. Most councils now have a private contractor
providing at least one of their main services.
Like privatisation, compulsory competitive tendering is a Tory policy which
came late, started slowly amid political controversy, but is coming to be
taken for granted by unions and opposition parties alike.
Labour fought the general election committed to end tendering - 'but by the
next election it will be a way of life', said one of the party's prominent
council leaders.
The result? A revolution in local authority culture - not least in the 41
per cent of councils in which the in-house labour force has so far won all
the main contracts.
For the first time in most authorities, the 'client' and 'contractor'
functions have been separated - divorcing the setting of standards and
monitoring of performance from the management of service delivery. One
leader of a large authority confessed that before compulsory competitive
tendering he did not even know how many staff the council employed.
Research by Mr Simon Domberger, an associate of the Institute for Fiscal
Studies, indicates that cost savings of about 20 per cent have been made by
putting refuse collection out to tender. The precise figure is disputed, but
none deny that real reductions have been achieved.
Mr Tom McGuirk, manager of the IPF's competitive tendering information
service, said: 'The definition of service standards as set out in contract
specifications largely did not exist prior to the introduction of compulsory
competitive tendering.'
With citizens' charters as profuse locally as nationally, standards look set
to be the refrain of the 1990s.
The Competitive Edge: Early Trends in CCT, CIPFA, 3 Robert St, London WC2N
6BH Pounds 75 (Pounds 50 to local authorities).
