<DOCNO>FT922-6261</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEZASADFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920526
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 92 / UK Council Services: A child of the streets turns upwardly
mobile
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE contracting-out culture is spreading far beyond services such as refuse
collection and street cleaning. Competitive tendering will extend across the
public services over the next few years into housing, care of the elderly,
health and education. It will also reach the Civil Service.
Services will be provided increasingly by independent organisations under
contract to councils, government departments, health authorities and other
public bodies. There will be opportunities for the private and voluntary
sectors to take over provision of services previously performed by public
monopolies.
Compulsory competitive tendering in local government is already due to be
extended beyond direct services to the public such as cleaning, catering and
vehicle maintenance. Core town-hall functions such as architecture, planning
and the collection of local taxes are being considered for contracting out
under legislation passed in the last parliament.
Contracting out such white-collar services presents an extra challenge
because defining and enforcing the quality of service is more complicated
than with emptying dustbins or mowing grass. Officials at the environment
department are considering more than 500 responses to a consultative paper.
The extension of contracting out may have to wait until councils have
introduced internal trading accounts which will make the costs of different
functions more transparent. Bidding is likely to involve the sort of
two-stage process developed for auctioning ITV contracts in which bidders
must first prove that they can reach a quality threshold before their bids
are considered.
The government is also keen for councils to contract out management of their
housing stock to housing associations and other private-sector
organisations. The introduction of community-care reforms next year will
make councils responsible for purchasing care for the elderly and
handicapped from a wide range of providers. Those will include the voluntary
and private sectors as well as the councils' social services departments.
Critics of compulsory competitive tendering claim that it has had only a
limited impact because most contracts are won by council workforces. This is
certainly the case, as figures from the Chartered Institute of Public
Finance and Accountancy show.
But even when the work stays in-house, the process of tendering shakes up
the service. The council workforce must defeat the opposition with a bid
which makes a 5 per cent rate of return on capital. This in effect turns it
into a semi-independent organisation in which managers must introduce new
working practices to reduce costs and improve the quality of service.
A similar revolution in contracting out is under way in the National Health
Service and central government. The government's reforms are turning health
authorities into commissioning bodies which buy in health care from NHS
hospitals, trust hospitals and even the private sector.
Even in Whitehall, radical moves are under way to contract out much of the
work of delivering central-government services. A white paper published in
November suggested that putting Civil Service functions out to tender could
save as much as 25 per cent of the cost of Pounds 20bn a year.
Some government support services such as security, photocopying and cleaning
have already been contracted out.
But the Treasury is now considering departmental plans for contracting out a
much wider range of clerical, administrative and professional functions. For
example, more than one in four of the 65,000 jobs in the Inland Revenue are
to be opened to 'market testing' this summer.
The role of government at national and central level will change as
contracting out spreads. Rather than being involved in the day-to-day
management of public services, it will assume a regulatory role, guarding
the public interest on matters such as service quality, prices (where there
are charges) and competition.
Altogether it amounts to the biggest shake-up in public services since the
post-war Labour government created the modern welfare state. Whether it will
succeed in delivering the improved services to which the government is
committed remains to be seen.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
