<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 92 / EC hitch ahead of Earth Summit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Community's prospects of taking a robust programme on global
warming to next week's Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro dimmed yesterday,
because of delays in finalising the details of the energy tax the European
Commission approved two weeks ago.
EC environment ministers meeting in Brussels today had been expected to give
provisional endorsement to the tax. But it became clear yesterday that the
draft directive on combatting carbon dioxide emissions is not yet ready.
This largely technical hold-up puts Mr Carlo Ripa di Meana, EC environment
commissioner, in a delicate position. The commissioner has repeatedly said
he will go to Rio only if he has a firm EC position to defend.
Such a position would have to include, Mr Ripa di Meana has said, support
from the Twelve for the Commission's energy tax; EC commitment to a near
doubling of development aid within the Climate Change convention due to be
signed in Rio; and resolution of the EC's two-year wrangle on where to
locate the European Environment Agency. It is not clear ministers can
resolve any of these issues today.
Member states such as the UK, while prepared to examine the case for a tax
to cut emissions, are unwilling to make a commitment until they see the
detailed implications. Spain, however, is concerned that an energy tax could
slow its industrial development.
But some northern states, led by Germany, support the tax and are angry the
Commission has made its proposal dependent on US and Japanese willingness to
adopt a similar anti-emissions strategy.
Carlo Ripa di Meana: Why Rio must deliver, Page 16
</TEXT>
