<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 92 / Mountleigh receivership deals blow to lenders: Barclays
among banks owed Pounds 400m by property group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON LONDON and VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RECEIVERS were called in yesterday at Mountleigh, one of the UK's biggest
property groups and owner of Spain's second biggest store chain, Galerias
Preciados.
Mountleigh, one of the UK's most ambitious companies in the 1980s, owes
Pounds 147m to bondholders and about Pounds 400m to banks, led by Barclays
of the UK and Citicorp of the US. Receivers and bankers could not quantify
yesterday the losses likely to be suffered by the company's creditors.
However, its receivership has dealt another severe blow to banks operating
in the UK, which expect to lose billions of pounds this year on their
exposure to the UK property market.
Mountleigh's receivership comes after months of attempts by the company and
its banks to prop it up. The receivership was triggered by the collapse of
attempts to raise funds by selling Merry Hill shopping centre in Dudley, in
the West Midlands, in order to make substantial payment to holders of Swiss
bonds.
It was due to repay SFr150m (Pounds 56m) tomorrow. Interest payments on
another bond issue were missed last week.
Mr Tim Hayward and Mr Stephen James of KPMG Peat Marwick, the accountancy
firm, were appointed yesterday to the main UK holding company. The decision
to appoint them followed the breakdown of talks with bank creditors on a
planned financial restructuring for the group.
A meeting of directors on Saturday decided the company could no longer
fulfil its debt obligations and the main bank creditors, led by Barclays and
Citicorp, were invited to appoint receivers. Other principal bankers are
thought to include Bankers Trust of the US, Credit Lyonnais of France,
Switzerland's Credit Suisse, Unibank from Denmark and three UK banks,
Lloyds, National Westminster and Royal Bank of Scotland.
All the bank debt is secured on the assets. The receivers said Mountleigh's
property portfolio was worth at least Pounds 400m.
Mr James said he expected Mountleigh's UK subsidiaries to follow the parent
into receivership. But receivers will probably not be appointed to Galerias
Preciados. Bankers flew to Spain at the weekend to reassure the subsidiary
it would continue to receive their financial support. Mr Hayward, in Madrid,
said the chain would have to be sold. A potential buyer has already made an
offer for the group, which last year had sales of Dollars 980m (Pounds
554m).
In the UK, the company is best known for the Merry Hill shopping
development, a shopping centre in Camberley, Surrey, and its half share in
the Criterion centre in London's Piccadilly. It also owns properties across
continental Europe, which are unaffected by the UK receivership.
Notices appeared yesterday in Swiss financial newspapers calling a meeting
of bondholders on June 10. Mountleigh was planning to ask investors to defer
all interest and principle repayments until July 31, when it had hoped to be
able to present a full debt restructuring plan.
However, the failure to reach agreement with secured bank creditors, which
rank above bondholders in the event of winding up, meant that a full
restructuring could not be achieved.
Mr James said the receivers would examine the assets of the company and
would 'consider an orderly disposal programme' so that creditors can be
repaid.
In the past three months, Olympia &amp; York, developer of Canary Wharf; Heron
International, a property and trading group; Speyhawk, a UK developer; and
Randsworth, a property investor, have run into serious financial trouble.
Citicorp and Barclays have big exposures to several of these companies.
In the 1980s, Mountleigh was transformed from a small wool maker into a
property company with a market value so high it felt able to bid Pounds 2bn
for Storehouse in 1987.
Prosaic end to property prodigy, Page 19
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 1
</PAGE>
