<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 92 / Companies urged to audit interim financial statements
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN and ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES will be urged to obtain audits of their interim financial
statements instead of relying on a single annual audit in a wide-ranging
report on corporate governance due out tomorrow.
The recommendation is to be included in the final draft report from the
Committee on the Financial Aspects of Corporate Governance, the chairman of
which is Sir Adrian Cadbury.
The recommendation, like many others in the report, is likely to spark
controversy both from those who feel it goes too far and from those who
believe it does not go far enough.
While many of its recommendations deal with the presentation of accounts, it
will urge a number of reforms to board structures, including a larger role
for non-executive directors with specific obligations towards shareholders.
It will also press for greater disclosure of certain kinds of information
beyond the corporate accounts.
While no company need comply with its recommendations, the report will urge
the Stock Exchange to adopt a new listing requirement to force companies at
least to disclose the extent to which they comply with the Cadbury
Committee's recommendations.
Since Sir Andrew Hugh Smith, the Stock Exchange chairman, is a member of the
committee and was instrumental in its establishment, the rule is expected to
be adopted.
The evolution of the committee, launched last spring, has its roots in the
accountancy profession. Mr Michael Lickiss, former chairman of the Institute
of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales, Sir Ron Dearing, chairman of
the Financial Reporting Council, and Sir Andrew Hugh Smith organised its
creation, galvanised partly by several well-publicised corporate collapses
which were nowhere reflected in their financial statements. The committee's
founders, therefore, felt the greatest reforms were needed in accountancy
and auditing procedures.
For instance, the committee's suggestion that interim statements be audited
comes as institutional investors are increasingly questioning the
reliability of corporate accounts between the audited periods. Earlier this
year, a call for the auditing of preliminary statements was issued by the
auditing committee of the Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and
Wales.
But Sir Ron said that, while the Cadbury Committee was being drawn up, its
founders realised that the structure of boards of directors and their
relationship with shareholders needed review as well.
The report is expected to include these recommendations:
Each board shall have separate audit and remuneration committees composed
entirely of non-executive directors - a move that could force all boards to
include at least two non-executives.
Performance-related pay elements of each director's remuneration shall be
disclosed.
Directors' terms of office should run for no more than three years.
Companies shall be required to make funds available to non-executive
directors wishing to get independent professional advice on certain
corporate matters.
Ways to make the annual general meeting a forum for small shareholders to
obtain information and voice their concerns.
Several of the recommendations are likely to disturb a large number of
directors. The investment company 3i, in a survey of finance directors at
some of the UK's largest companies, found that 82 per cent opposed giving
shareholders representation on remuneration committees, while 78 per cent
opposed their representation on audit committees. A number of the Cadbury
report's suggestions have been opposed by the Confederation of British
Industry.
However, the report is likely to fall short of what had been sought by the
more hawkish institutional investors, some of which have urged that
directors' remuneration packages and terms of office be disclosed annually
and that US-style accounting reports be introduced to help shareholders
learn more about the profitability of corporate subsidiaries. It is also
likely to fall short of what some Labour MPs had hoped for.
</TEXT>
