FT  26 MAY 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Television produces precious few programmes which last as little as five
minutes, but today sees the start of Dance House (8.25 BBC2), a series of 12
short films within the 'Commissions and Collaborations' season 'designed to
show the diversity of British dance today.' Today's opening offering is
'Mosaic,' a monologue written by Anthony Minghella, with choreography by
Jonathan Lunn, featuring dancer Lauren Potter and actress Juliet Stevenson.
There is another collectively awful party in the final episode of ITV's
superb Anglo-Saxon Attitudes (8.30), this time given by Robin and
Marie-Helene, and gate-crashed by .. Well, wait and see.
Rear Window, Channel 4's series about arts and race, features the work of
children's writer, Geoffrey Trease, who, at 88, is about to finish his 102nd
novel (9.00).
Some of the lines in BBC1's 60-minute comedy-drama series, Boys from the
Bush (9.30) are a bit weak, but the situations, such as Arlene's wedding in
Delilah's brothel last week, are often very funny. BBC2's highly informative
documentary series, The Racing Game , looks at horse-breeding (9.50).
</TEXT>
